{"type":"item.started","item":{"id":"item_1","type":"command_execution","command":"/bin/zsh -lc \"sed -n '1,220p' /Users/david/.codex/memories/skills/adversarial-review-contract/SKILL.md && sed -n '1,220p' /Users/david/.codex/memories/MEMORY.md\"","aggregated_output":"","exit_code":null,"status":"in_progress"}}
{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_1","type":"command_execution","command":"/bin/zsh -lc \"sed -n '1,220p' /Users/david/.codex/memories/skills/adversarial-review-contract/SKILL.md && sed -n '1,220p' /Users/david/.codex/memories/MEMORY.md\"","aggregated_output":"---\nname: adversarial-review-contract\ndescription: Use for read-only adversarial reviews where the user wants exact anchors, live-source verification, terse findings, and a fixed verdict contract.\nargument-hint: \"[spec-or-task-scope]\"\nuser-invocable: false\nallowed-tools:\n  - Read\n  - Grep\n  - Bash\n---\n\n# Adversarial Review Contract\n\nUse this when the user asks for read-only review language such as \"adversarial review\", \"read-only\", \"no file edits\", \"do not infer\", \"grep and read\", \"find every way this fails\", or requires exact anchors/citations.\n\nDo not use this for implementation tasks or for reviews that allow speculative design advice.\n\n## Inputs / context to gather\n\n1. Read the user prompt and extract the exact output contract.\n2. Read the target spec/task/plan files first.\n3. Read the exact live repo files or exact git object paths that the review must verify.\n4. If the user names required commands, run those exact commands and use their output as evidence anchors.\n5. If this is a re-review, read the prior review or decision log only after you know the current task scope.\n6. If the review is governed by a spec or success-criteria doc, extract that checklist up front and use it as the coverage map for the review.\n\n## Procedure\n\n1. Lock mode to read-only.\n   - Do not edit files.\n   - Do not propose code changes as if they were already verified.\n2. Build a verification table before writing findings.\n   - Task/spec anchor.\n   - Live source path and line.\n   - Status: correct, incomplete, drifted, or missing.\n3. Verify anchors against the live repo, not just plan prose.\n   - Grep the exact anchor text first.\n   - If the file or anchor is missing, say so explicitly.\n4. Trace the runtime consequence for any nontrivial finding.\n   - Example: if a merge plan moves features, also inspect the read path that decides visibility.\n5. For seam-heavy data flows, trace both the write path and every public read/query surface that can surface the behavior.\n   - Typical seam order: normalization, storage codec/insert bindings, hydration/replay, then public read or recall APIs.\n6. Drop weak claims.\n   - If a claim lacks an exact citation, remove it.\n   - If a claim depends on inference beyond the spec/diff/source, downgrade it or drop it.\n7. For re-reviews, grep nearby plan files for stale drift.\n   - Check top-level `plan.md`, decision logs, sibling tasks, and ledger text when the user asks for \"new inconsistency\" or \"all references gone\".\n8. Write the final answer in the exact requested format.\n   - Findings first.\n   - Terse wording.\n   - Exactly one verdict line in the requested wording.\n\n## Efficiency plan\n\n- Start with the user-named files and commands; do not roam the repo first.\n- Use fixed-string grep for anchors before opening large files.\n- Cache the exact paths and line numbers for each finding in a scratch list so you do not have to re-open the same files.\n- Stop searching a candidate issue once it loses citation support; move to the next axis.\n\n## Pitfalls and fixes\n\n- Symptom: the review sounds persuasive but has no surviving findings.\n  - Cause: claims were not tied to exact lines.\n  - Fix: enforce \"no citation, no finding.\"\n- Symptom: the task file looks corrected but the plan is still inconsistent.\n  - Cause: only the named task file was checked.\n  - Fix: grep the wider plan tree for semantic drift.\n- Symptom: an anchor matches, but the implementation would still fail.\n  - Cause: anchor-only verification missed downstream runtime behavior.\n  - Fix: inspect the live read/query path affected by the change.\n- Symptom: a storage/query feature looks correct in one seam but still fails the success criteria.\n  - Cause: only one branch or one consumer was inspected.\n  - Fix: map the spec criteria first, then walk string vs array branches and each public consumer that can expose the data.\n- Symptom: output drifts into praise or summary.\n  - Cause: the fixed review contract was not followed.\n  - Fix: write only concrete findings plus the exact verdict line.\n\n## Verification checklist\n\n- The answer stays read-only.\n- Every finding cites the exact task/spec anchor and the exact source or git-output line.\n- When a spec defines success criteria, the reviewed findings explicitly cover or defer each relevant criterion.\n- Missing files or anchors are called out explicitly.\n- Plan-text conclusions are separated from source-backed verification when the user asks for that distinction.\n- The final line uses the exact verdict wording requested by the user.\n\n## Minimal usage example\n\nIf the user asks for a read-only adversarial review of `$ARGUMENTS`:\n\n1. Read the target task/spec files.\n2. Read the named source files or `git show` output.\n3. Keep only findings that survive exact citation.\n4. Return the requested findings format and verdict line.\n# Task Group: cron-run-now-ux adversarial breakdown reviews in WednesdayAI core\n\nscope: Read-only breakdown/spec reviews for `cron-run-now-ux`, with exact `file:line` citations, success-criteria coverage checks, and live source verification of plan mechanics in this worktree.\napplies_to: cwd=/Users/david/Code/WednesdayAI-core/.claude/worktrees/bridge-cse_01NJe2jAd1ntFWrEps3Yhrr4; reuse_rule=safe for similar citation-bound cron breakdown reviews in this WednesdayAI-core worktree family, but treat exact anchors, task ordering, and line numbers as checkout-specific\n\n## Task 1: Cron-run-now-ux breakdown review found SC6 timing drift and missing `CronState` fixture coverage\n\n### rollout_summary_files\n\n- rollout_summaries/2026-06-29T04-15-51-pGjH-cron_run_now_ux_adversarial_breakdown_review.md (cwd=/Users/david/Code/WednesdayAI-core/.claude/worktrees/bridge-cse_01NJe2jAd1ntFWrEps3Yhrr4, rollout_path=/Users/david/.codex/sessions/2026/06/29/rollout-2026-06-29T14-15-51-019f1197-3a58-7b62-86d0-79defe0477a5.jsonl, updated_at=2026-06-29T04:19:37+00:00, thread_id=019f1197-3a58-7b62-86d0-79defe0477a5, returned `VERDICT: REVISE` after finding blocking timing drift and omitted typed fixtures)\n\n### keywords\n\n- cron-run-now-ux, adversarial breakdown review, VERDICT: REVISE, SC6, CronState, sessionKey, ops.run, executeJobCoreWithTimeout, ui/src/ui/views/cron.ts, tsconfig.json, exact anchors\n\n## Task 2: Verdict contract execution for citation-bound breakdown reviews\n\n### rollout_summary_files\n\n- rollout_summaries/2026-06-29T04-15-51-pGjH-cron_run_now_ux_adversarial_breakdown_review.md (cwd=/Users/david/Code/WednesdayAI-core/.claude/worktrees/bridge-cse_01NJe2jAd1ntFWrEps3Yhrr4, rollout_path=/Users/david/.codex/sessions/2026/06/29/rollout-2026-06-29T14-15-51-019f1197-3a58-7b62-86d0-79defe0477a5.jsonl, updated_at=2026-06-29T04:19:37+00:00, thread_id=019f1197-3a58-7b62-86d0-79defe0477a5, useful for exact numbered-findings plus verdict formatting)\n\n### keywords\n\n- attack the BREAKDOWN, not code, numbered CITED findings, VERDICT: REVISE, success-criteria coverage, exact fix requirements, read actual repo files\n\n## User preferences\n\n- when the user said \"ADVERSARIAL BREAKDOWN REVIEW — no code written yet. Attack the BREAKDOWN, not code.\" -> keep similar reviews focused on decomposition, dependency ordering, and coverage defects rather than implementation advice [Task 1]\n- when the user said \"Read actual repo files (do not guess)\" and required numbered cited findings ending with `VERDICT: APPROVE` or `VERDICT: REVISE` -> verify live source before judging the plan and keep the final output terse and citation-bound [Task 1][Task 2]\n- when the user’s checklist demanded live verification of each claimed anchor and success-criteria coverage -> build a coverage map from the frozen spec before trusting `covers_criteria` claims in the plan tree [Task 1]\n\n## Reusable knowledge\n\n- In this workstream, `src/cron/service/ops.ts` still blocks until `executeJobCoreWithTimeout` returns, and `src/gateway/server-methods/cron.ts` passes the `cron.run` result through verbatim, so a session link cannot appear during the run unless the session key becomes available before the RPC resolves [Task 1]\n- `ui/src/ui/views/cron.ts` currently renders the session banner only when `!props.busy && props.lastRunSessionKey`; if the spec promises an in-flight link, review both the busy guard and when `sessionKey` is captured [Task 1]\n- `tsconfig.json` includes `ui/**/*`, so UI controller fixtures that construct full `CronState` objects are part of the real typecheck surface even if a task file omits them from its file list [Task 1]\n- The durable review sequence here is: spec -> plan -> phase task files -> decisions ledger -> live server flow -> UI/controller fixtures -> `covers_criteria` / manual verification claims [Task 1]\n- Related skill: skills/adversarial-review-contract/SKILL.md [Task 1][Task 2]\n\n## Failures and how to do differently\n\n- Symptom: a plan claims SC6 is covered by one UI task, but the session-link behavior still depends on a later plumbing task. Cause: the review trusted `covers_criteria` mapping without checking when data becomes available in the live control flow. Fix: trace the end-to-end timing path from RPC start to UI render before accepting the mapping [Task 1]\n- Symptom: a state-field change looks scoped to one UI file, but typecheck will still fail elsewhere. Cause: typed test fixtures constructing the full state shape were omitted from the breakdown. Fix: search for direct `CronState` fixtures and include them whenever the state contract changes [Task 1]\n- Symptom: plan prose sounds plausible enough to approve. Cause: the review did not compare the frozen spec promise against the blocking runtime path and the UI guard together. Fix: verify the spec promise, live source behavior, and task ordering as one dependency chain [Task 1]\n\n# Task Group: delivery-reliability adversarial reviews in WednesdayAI core\n\nscope: Read-only plan-vs-source adversarial review of the `delivery-reliability` workstream, with exact `file:line` citations, spec/task/source cross-checking, and checkout-specific anchor validation in this worktree.\napplies_to: cwd=/Users/david/Code/WednesdayAI-core/.claude/worktrees/bridge-cse_014fkbXAg8R9eRzQKW4UnTCT; reuse_rule=safe for similar read-only delivery-reliability reviews in this WednesdayAI-core worktree family, but treat exact anchors, config state, and live line numbers as checkout-specific\n\n## Task 1: PR #240 outbound-delivery reviews converged from an initial `bestEffort` concern to one surviving docs mismatch\n\n### rollout_summary_files\n\n- rollout_summaries/2026-06-29T00-30-10-jBn4-pr240_outbound_delivery_adversarial_review_revise.md (cwd=/Users/david/Code/WednesdayAI-core/.claude/worktrees/bridge-cse_014fkbXAg8R9eRzQKW4UnTCT, rollout_path=/Users/david/.codex/sessions/2026/06/29/rollout-2026-06-29T10-30-10-019f10c8-9b58-7720-8f63-1a44ace735d2.jsonl, updated_at=2026-06-29T00:33:09+00:00, thread_id=019f10c8-9b58-7720-8f63-1a44ace735d2, round-2 review kept only the operator-doc mismatch and ended `VERDICT: REVISE`)\n- rollout_summaries/2026-06-29T00-02-31-MGKA-pr_240_delivery_reliability_adversarial_review.md (cwd=/Users/david/Code/WednesdayAI-core/.claude/worktrees/bridge-cse_014fkbXAg8R9eRzQKW4UnTCT, rollout_path=/Users/david/.codex/sessions/2026/06/29/rollout-2026-06-29T10-02-31-019f10af-4cf4-78e1-8bba-b6f95a86e6d0.jsonl, updated_at=2026-06-29T00:07:45+00:00, thread_id=019f10af-4cf4-78e1-8bba-b6f95a86e6d0, earlier pass found a `bestEffort`/`onError` blocker that the later re-review did not confirm)\n\n### keywords\n\n- PR #240, outbound delivery, docs/gateway/outbound-delivery.md, docs/docs.json, SC1, SC2, SC3, SC4, SC5, SC6, d