keywords\n\n- delivery-reliability, adversarial review, VERDICT: REVISE, exact anchors, file:line citations, deliver.ts, delivery-queue.ts, deliver.test.ts, outbound.test.ts, tsconfig.json, .oxlintrc.json, oxlint --print-config, Error.cause, failDelivery, recoverPendingDeliveries\n\n## Task 4: Review workflow cues for exact-anchor delivery-reliability audits\n\n### rollout_summary_files\n\n- rollout_summaries/2026-06-29T00-30-10-jBn4-pr240_outbound_delivery_adversarial_review_revise.md (cwd=/Users/david/Code/WednesdayAI-core/.claude/worktrees/bridge-cse_014fkbXAg8R9eRzQKW4UnTCT, rollout_path=/Users/david/.codex/sessions/2026/06/29/rollout-2026-06-29T10-30-10-019f10c8-9b58-7720-8f63-1a44ace735d2.jsonl, updated_at=2026-06-29T00:33:09+00:00, thread_id=019f10c8-9b58-7720-8f63-1a44ace735d2, reinforced full-file reading, exact verdict line, and carve-out handling)\n- rollout_summaries/2026-06-29T00-02-31-MGKA-pr_240_delivery_reliability_adversarial_review.md (cwd=/Users/david/Code/WednesdayAI-core/.claude/worktrees/bridge-cse_014fkbXAg8R9eRzQKW4UnTCT, rollout_path=/Users/david/.codex/sessions/2026/06/29/rollout-2026-06-29T10-02-31-019f10af-4cf4-78e1-8bba-b6f95a86e6d0.jsonl, updated_at=2026-06-29T00:07:45+00:00, thread_id=019f10af-4cf4-78e1-8bba-b6f95a86e6d0, added the report-file deliverable and mechanics-vs-fidelity review lens)\n- rollout_summaries/2026-06-28T21-13-54-ruzP-delivery_reliability_adversarial_review_exact_source_checks.md (cwd=/Users/david/Code/WednesdayAI-core/.claude/worktrees/bridge-cse_014fkbXAg8R9eRzQKW4UnTCT, rollout_path=/Users/david/.codex/sessions/2026/06/29/rollout-2026-06-29T07-13-54-019f1014-ecdf-7d01-9fd8-fec46e7b9b1d.jsonl, updated_at=2026-06-28T21:18:21+00:00, thread_id=019f1014-ecdf-7d01-9fd8-fec46e7b9b1d, useful review order and lint-rule proof sequence)\n\n### keywords\n\n- read-only, one pass, attack these five correctness traps, Before: anchor, plan-vs-source verification, spec success criteria, sibling checkout, node_modules absent, no speculation, mechanically auditable output\n\n## User preferences\n\n- when the user said \"Adversarial review\", \"code NOT yet written\", and \"Do not ask clarifying questions. Read every file, perform every check, and produce the full verdict in one pass\" -> default to read-only, exhaustive, one-pass review without routine clarification [Task 1][Task 2]\n- when the user said \"Every finding must cite file:line from the actual source\" and \"No speculation\" -> keep only claims that survive live source lines; uncited claims are not findings [Task 1]\n- when the user said \"Read all listed files completely before forming findings\" and \"Do not report a finding you cannot cite with specific file:line evidence\" -> full-file reading is the default for similar re-reviews, even when the prompt highlights likely failure areas [Task 1][Task 3]\n- when the user explicitly excluded standing debt like \"F2 and F7\" -> honor the carve-out and do not re-flag accepted debt as a fresh finding [Task 1]\n- when the user required the review to be written to `.agents/reports/2026-06-29-1-codex-delivery-review.md` and then returned -> plan for a file-backed deliverable in similar review tasks, but verify the destination early if the path sits under `.agents` [Task 2][Task 4]\n- when the user asked for both mechanics and fidelity lenses -> check correctness and success-criteria coverage separately rather than collapsing them into one judgment [Task 1][Task 4]\n- when the user said \"For every 'Before:' anchor quoted in any of the four task files, locate the exact current lines in the real source\" and treated whitespace/identifier drift as real mismatches -> make anchor checks mechanical and conservative rather than approximate [Task 1]\n- when the user asked to \"Attack these five correctness traps\" instead of stopping after the first issue -> complete the full requested checklist even if an early finding already looks blocking [Task 3][Task 4]\n\n## Reusable knowledge\n\n- The efficient review order for this worktree is: spec/plan/task docs -> live `src/infra/outbound` source -> tests -> `tsconfig.json` / `.oxlintrc.json` / `package.json` -> exact-anchor cross-checks [Task 3]\n- `docs/superpowers/specs/2026-06-28-delivery-reliability.md` is the frozen contract for this workstream; T201/T301/T302 should be checked against spec success criteria, not treated as self-validating plan truth [Task 3]\n- `pnpm tsgo` and `pnpm test --run src/infra/outbound/delivery-error.test.ts src/infra/outbound/deliver.test.ts src/infra/outbound/outbound.test.ts` both passed in the initial PR #240 review, so that command pair is a good focused proof set for this outbound surface even though it does not prove logic correctness by itself [Task 1]\n- This checkout uses `target: \"es2023\"` and `lib: [\"DOM\", \"DOM.Iterable\", \"ES2023\", \"ScriptHost\"]`, so native `Error.cause` is type-compatible here [Task 3]\n- `.oxlintrc.json` is the checked-in oxlint config in this repo, and the useful proof command for rule-activation questions is `oxlint --print-config --config .oxlintrc.json --type-aware`; the effective Oxlint 1.50.0 config here showed `typescript/no-floating-promises: deny` and `typescript/no-meaningless-void-operator: deny` while `eslint/no-void` was not enabled [Task 1][Task 3]\n- `src/infra/outbound/deliver.ts` still contains the silent queue-write catch and silent flush catches described by T201, but the outer failure path rethrows after queue cleanup; review the inner catches and the outer catch separately [Task 3]\n- `deliver.ts` best-effort queue-write failure is implemented as `enqueueDelivery(...).catch(...)` that logs a warning and returns `null`, then the send still proceeds; operator docs must match that best-effort behavior rather than claim the message was never dispatched [Task 1]\n- `failDelivery` concurrency is implemented by an in-process `serializeByKey(filePath, task)` chain in `delivery-queue.ts`, and tests cover concurrent increments plus the terminal flush path [Task 1]\n- `DeliveryError` is the structured queue-layer error type, `isDeliveryError` is the discriminator, and `DeliveryError.from(err)` is intentionally idempotent for existing `DeliveryError` instances [Task 1]\n- `docs/docs.json` contains `gateway/outbound-delivery` in the published nav tree, so mismatches in `docs/gateway/outbound-delivery.md` affect the operator docs surface rather than dead documentation [Task 1]\n- Worktree-level access can still reject `.agents/*` writes even when source reads, `git status`, and other worktree operations succeed; treat requested report destinations under `.agents` as a separate permission check [Task 2]\n- `src/infra/outbound/delivery-queue.ts:127-141` is the live `failDelivery` body under T301, and `src/infra/outbound/outbound.test.ts` still keeps `describe(\"failDelivery\")` immediately before `describe(\"moveToFailed\")`, so the task landmarks were current in this checkout [Task 3]\n- Related skill: skills/adversarial-review-contract/SKILL.md [Task 1][Task 3][Task 4]\n\n## Failures and how to do differently\n\n- Symptom: a prompt-highlighted logic hole looks real after the first read. Cause: the review preserved a hypothesis before reconciling it with the later live-code pass. Fix: when iterative PR reviews disagree, keep the newer line-cited result and mark the older concern as superseded unless the exact code still supports it; here the later re-review cleared the `bestEffort`/`onError` blocker and left only docs drift [Task 1]\n- Symptom: a requested report artifact is assumed writable because the worktree is otherwise accessible. Cause: destination-specific sandbox policy on `.agents/reports`. Fix: verify writability of the requested output path early and be ready to return the report inline if `.agents/*` is blocked [Task 2]\n- Symptom: a plan/ledger looks internally coherent, so the review assumes the task is fine. Cause: the review treated the plan as truth instead of checking the frozen spec. Fix: compare T201/T301/T302 against `docs/superpowers/specs/2026-06-28-delivery-reliability.md` first and flag contract mismatches early; here the plan chose log-and-return-null for queue-write failure even though the spec required caller-visible error or metric accounting [Task 3]\n- Symptom: operator docs sound plausible, so the review preserves them as correct. Cause: the review checked prose without confirming implementation and test behavior together. Fix: cross-check `docs/gateway/outbound-delivery.md` against both code and tests before reporting a docs finding or approving the docs surface [Task 1]\n- Symptom: rule-activation claims about `no-floating-promises`, `void tail.finally(...)`, or `no-void` become speculative. Cause: the review stopped at the flat config file or lacked local `node_modules`. Fix: answer from the checked-in config first, and if rule introspection is still needed, use a sibling checkout’s installed `oxlint --print-config` while citing only the current checkout’s config files [Task 1][Task 3]\n- Symptom: anchor-comparison helpers fail in the read-only sandbox. Cause: the environment blocks ad hoc here-doc scratch scripts. Fix: rely on direct numbered output and mechanical line checks instead of temporary script helpers [Task 1]\n- Symptom: prompt-highlighted mechanics concerns keep consuming review time even after reading the relevant code. Cause: the review kept chasing hypotheses that the exact lines had already disproved. Fix: once live code clears a hinted risk, drop it and preserve only the surviving cited defect [Task 1][Task 4]\n- Symptom: prose drafting outruns evidence and later loses support. Cause: findings were written before the exact line list was stable. Fix: keep a scratch table of task/spec anchor -> live source line -> status, and only draft after every surviving claim has a citation [Task 1][Task 4]\n\n# Task Group: context-engine proactive-topic-recall adversarial re-reviews in MondayDev\n\nscope: Narrow re-reviews of prior findings in `docs/plans/context-engine-proactive-topic-recall`, with exact citations, local-branch freshness checks, and mechanical TypeScript program-shape verification in this worktree.\napplies_to: cwd=/Users/david/Code/MondayDev/.claude/worktrees/bridge-cse_01JBFBSbyEG9dDgAg1s2u2HC; reuse_rule=safe for similar read-only re-reviews in this MondayDev worktree family, but treat exact commits, plan anchors, and config state as checkout-specific\n\n## Task 1: Re-review confirmed SC6 now matches the slice-then-escape implementation\n\n### rollout_summary_files\n\n- rollout_summaries/2026-06-28T13-25-25-JZhg-context_engine_proactive_topic_recall_round2_rereview.md (cwd=/Users/david/Code/MondayDev/.claude/worktrees/bridge-cse_01JBFBSbyEG9dDgAg1s2u2HC, rollout_path=/Users/david/.codex/sessions/2026/06/28/rollout-2026-06-28T23-25-25-019f0e68-02d4-7321-bb28-d60ef824074a.jsonl, updated_at=2026-06-28T13:41:01+00:00, thread_id=019f0e68-02d4-7321-bb28-d60ef824074a, round-2 re-review cleared the prior SC6 mismatch)\n\n### keywords\n\n- context-engine proactive-topic-recall, round-2 re-review, SC6, slice-then-escape, safeLabel, collect.ts, queryText.length === 100, &lt;script&gt;, APPROVE\n\n## Task 2: Re-review proved the prior `topicRecall` typecheck blocker is no longer real under the actual TS gate\n\n### rollout_summary_files\n\n- rollout_summaries/2026-06-28T13-25-25-JZhg-context_engine_proactive_topic_recall_round2_rereview.md (cwd=/Users/david/Code/MondayDev/.claude/worktrees/bridge-cse_01JBFBSbyEG9dDgAg1s2u2HC, rollout_path=/Users/david/.codex/sessions/2026/06/28/rollout-2026-06-28T23-25-25-019f0e68-02d4-7321-bb28-d60ef824074a.jsonl, updated_at=2026-06-28T13:41:01+00:00, thread_id=019f0e68-02d4-7321-bb28-d60ef824074a, `tsconfig.test.json` program-shape check downgraded the prior blocker)\n\n### keywords\n\n- ContextEngineConfig, topicRecall, tsconfig.test.json, tsconfig.json, npx --no-install tsc, --showConfig, --listFiles, test/**/* excluded, CONFIRMED SAFE\n\n## User preferences\n\n- when the user said \"Re-review round 2\" and \"re-check ONLY these two prior findings\" -> keep re-reviews tightly scoped to the named findings and do not add fresh issues outside scope [Task 1][Task 2]\n- when the user asked to \"Run git pull or git fetch to get the latest state\" before re-reviewing -> try to refresh branch state first, but continue from the local branch tip if sandbox write limits block `FETCH_HEAD` and the requested commit is already present [Task 1]\n- when the user asked for a \"mechanical\" explanation of why TypeScript would or would not error -> prove the actual program shape with compiler evidence instead of offering a plausibility argument [Task 2]\n- when the user requested clear final states like `CONFIRMED SAFE` vs `STILL BLOCKING` -> classify the result explicitly and avoid hedged wrap-up text [Task 2]\n\n## Reusable knowledge\n\n- In this worktree, the updated SC6 test text now matches the implementation shape `String(topic.label).slice(0, 100).replace(...)`; the fastest comparison is the SC6 test block and inserted `collect.ts` block inside `docs/plans/context-engine-proactive-topic-recall/phase-1/002-topic-recall-sweep.md` [Task 1]\n- `safeLabel` is reused for both `queryText` and the heading text in the proposed implementation, so slice-before-escape correctness should be checked on both outputs together [Task 1]\n- `tsconfig.test.json` extends `tsconfig.json`, and the parent `exclude: [\"node_modules\", \"test/**/*\"]` means the apparent `include: [\"test/**/*.ts\"]` does not make those test files part of the final TS program in this gate [Task 2]\n- `npx --no-install tsc -p tsconfig.test.json --noEmit --pretty false` plus `--showConfig` and `--listFiles` is the reliable proof sequence here; it avoids network fetches and shows whether the disputed files are actually in-program [Task 2]\n- The prior `topicRecall` fixture-literal concern became non-blocking because `test/collect.test.ts` and `test/prune.test.ts` are excluded from the effective TS program, not because the interface was necessarily updated [Task 2]\n- Related skill: skills/adversarial-review-contract/SKILL.md [Task 1][Task 2]\n\n## Failures and how to do differently\n\n- Symptom: `git fetch origin feature/next-work` fails in sandbox before the re-review starts. Cause: the worktree cannot write `FETCH_HEAD`. Fix: verify whether the requested commit is already present locally and continue from the local branch tip if it is [Task 1][Task 2]\n- Symptom: a claimed TS blocker sounds plausible from plan text or fixture literals. Cause: the review skipped the merged compiler config and real program file set. Fix: run `npx --no-install tsc ...`, then inspect `--showConfig` and `--listFiles` before preserving the blocker [Task 2]\n- Symptom: an SC/test mismatch finding lingers after a plan update. Cause: the re-review compared old narrative expectations instead of the updated line pair. Fix: compare the current task-file test block directly against the current implementation block and drop the finding if they now align [Task 1]\n\n# Task Group: exact-anchored task-file preflight gating in WednesdayAI core\n\nscope: Constrained implementation tasks where the task file requires `grep -n` anchor checks, byte-for-byte Before-text validation, hard file boundaries, and stop-on-mismatch behavior across WednesdayAI worktrees.\napplies_to: cwd=/Users/david/Code/WednesdayAI-core/.claude/worktrees/*; reuse_rule=safe for similar exact-task execution workflows across WednesdayAI-core worktrees, but treat exact file contents, anchors, and task files as checkout-specific\n\n## Task 1: Realtime-voice status-handler task stopped because every Before block mismatched the current worktree\n\n### rollout_summary_files\n\n- rollout_summaries/2026-06-26T05-27-36-BsjV-realtime_voice_status_handler_preflight_mismatch.md (cwd=/Users/david/Code/WednesdayAI-core/.claude/worktrees/bridge-cse_01TqTmGiwGcMBDaoM9xJpMQ4, rollout_path=/Users/david/.codex/sessions/2026/06/26/rollout-2026-06-26T15-27-36-019f0265-d7e9-7d82-92db-1025956079ab.jsonl, updated_at=2026-06-26T05:29:34+00:00, thread_id=019f0265-d7e9-7d82-92db-1025956079ab, stopped before edits after five anchor mismatches)\n\n### keywords\n\n- realtime-voice-phase2, 007-status-handler-registration, grep -n, byte-for-byte Before-text, talk.realtime.status, talkHandlers['talk.realtime.status'], non-null assertion, stopReason, files: boundary\n\n## Task 2: Workspacelanes sandbox-fence task stopped because the tree was partially pre-applied and the task file no longer matched\n\n### rollout_summary_files\n\n- rollout_summaries/2026-06-26T05-42-02-SjGQ-sandbox_fence_to_lane_preflight_mismatch.md (cwd=/Users/david/Code/WednesdayAI-core/.claude/worktrees/workspacelanes-phase2-slice3, rollout_path=/Users/david/.codex/sessions/2026/06/26/rollout-2026-06-26T15-42-02-019f0273-0cbe-7093-aa01-16b0b552accc.jsonl, updated_at=2026-06-26T05:44:03+00:00, thread_id=019f0273-0cbe-7093-aa01-16b0b552accc, stopped after 4/5 exact block mismatches in a partially pre-applied tree)\n\n### keywords\n\n- workspacelanes phase2, sandbox-fence-to-lane-enforce, preflight, grep, anchor mismatch, fenceToLane?: boolean, WorkspaceLaneResolution, workspaceLane: params.workspaceLane, Zero undictated choices\n\n## User preferences\n\n- when the user said \"Execute the given task file EXACTLY and nothing more\" / \"Execute task file EXACTLY and nothing more\" -> treat the task file as the controlling spec, not a flexible implementation prompt [Task 1][Task 2]\n- when the user said \"Touch ONLY the files listed in the task's files: section\" or required \"Zero undictated choices — any deviation → STOP\" -> treat the `files:` list as a hard edit boundary and stop instead of expanding scope [Task 1][Task 2]\n- when the user said \"PRE-FLIGHT: for EACH file in the task, run grep -n ... If ANY anchor is absent or differs -> STOP\" -> exact anchor/Before-text validation is a blocking