Weaver compositional skill routing pipeline\\n     7\\t(Gao 2026, arXiv:2606.18051) using the `context.collect` lifecycle hook — the same seam\\n     8\\t`memory-lancedb` uses for auto-recall. The plugin injects retrieved skill descriptions into the\\n     9\\t**conversation** (not the system prompt), preserving the system prompt cache.\\n    10\\t\\n    11\\tEach phase is a shippable, testable tracer-bullet increment:\\n    12\\t- **Phase 1** — the extension loads and validates config (proves the shell works)\\n    13\\t- **Phase 2** — embedding backends produce vectors (proves all 3 backends)\\n    14\\t- **Phase 3** — skills are indexed and searchable (proves hnswlib integration)\\n    15\\t- **Phase 4** — SAD decomposition pipeline runs against a real LLM (proves the core algorithm)\\n    16\\t- **Phase 5** — full pipeline fires on every agent turn via `context.collect` (proves hook wiring)\\n    17\\t- **Phase 6** — error resilience and lifecycle management (proves production readiness)\\n    18\\t- **Phase 7** — benchmark suite and integration tests (proves SC achievement)\\n    19\\t\\n    20\\t## Phases\\n    21\\t\\n    22\\t| # | Phase | Task count | dep: | conflicts: |\\n    23\\t|---|-------|-----------|------|------------|\\n    24\\t| 1 | Plugin Shell | 001 002 003 | - | none |\\n    25\\t| 2 | Embedding Layer | 004 005 006 007 | - | none |\\n    26\\t| 3 | Skill Index | 008 009 | - | none |\\n    27\\t| 4 | Decomposition & Retrieval | 010 011 | - | none |\\n    28\\t| 5 | Hook Integration | 012 013 014 | - | none |\\n    29\\t| 6 | Resilience & Edge Cases | 015 016 | - | none |\\n    30\\t| 7 | Benchmark & Verification | 017 018 | - | none |\\n    31\\t\\n    32\\t## Task dependency matrix\\n    33\\t\\n    34\\t| Id | Phase | Title | dep: | conflicts: |\\n    35\\t|----|-------|-------|------|------------|\\n    36\\t| 001 | 1 | Extension package scaffolding | dep: - | conflicts: none |\\n    37\\t| 002 | 1 | Config schema resolver + validator | dep: 001 | conflicts: none |\\n    38\\t| 003 | 1 | Plugin entry point + config warning | dep: 002 | conflicts: none |\\n    39\\t| 004 | 2 | EmbeddingBackend interface + types | dep: 001 | conflicts: none |\\n    40\\t| 005 | 2 | LocalEmbedding backend | dep: 004 | conflicts: none |\\n    41\\t| 006 | 2 | CloudEmbedding backend | dep: 004 | conflicts: none |\\n    42\\t| 007 | 2 | CustomEmbedding backend | dep: 004 | conflicts: none |\\n    43\\t| 008 | 3 | SkillIndex build + search | dep: 001 004 | conflicts: none |\\n    44\\t| 009 | 3 | Index rebuild on fs change | dep: 008 | conflicts: none |\\n    45\\t| 010 | 4 | Decomposer + SAD prompts | dep: 002 | conflicts: none |\\n    46\\t| 011 | 4 | Retriever + hint construction | dep: 008 010 | conflicts: none |\\n    47\\t| 012 | 5 | ContextInjector formatting | dep: 001 | conflicts: none |\\n    48\\t| 013 | 5 | context.collect handler | dep: 003 008 010 011 012 | conflicts: none |\\n    49\\t| 014 | 5 | Full register() wiring | dep: 003 004 008 010 011 012 013 | conflicts: none |\\n    50\\t| 015 | 6 | Error resilience | dep: 013 014 | conflicts: none |\\n    51\\t| 016 | 6 | Lifecycle management | dep: 014 | conflicts: none |\\n    52\\t| 017 | 7 | Benchmark harness | dep: 011 | conflicts: none |\\n    53\\t| 018 | 7 | Integration tests | dep: 016 | conflicts: none |\",\"exit_code\":0,\"status\":\"completed\"}}\ndocs/plans/plugin-skillweaver/reviews/tournament-r1-codex.raw.log:26:{\"type\":\"item.completed\",\"item\":{\"id\":\"item_13\",\"type\":\"command_execution\",\"command\":\"/bin/zsh -lc 'nl -ba docs/superpowers/specs/2026-07-06-plugin-skillweaver.md'\",\"aggregated_output\":\"     1\\t---\\n     2\\tdoc_type: spec\\n     3\\tstatus: active\\n     4\\tid: TRK-005\\n     5\\tworkstream: plugin-skillweaver\\n     6\\tchange_kind: behaviour\\n     7\\ttitle: \\\"Plugin: SkillWeaver — Compositional Skill Routing for WednesdayAI\\\"\\n     8\\tcreated: 2026-07-06\\n     9\\tupdated: 2026-07-06\\n    10\\tauthor: david\\n    11\\ttags: [plugin, extension, skills, routing, retrieval, decomposition]\\n    12\\t---\\n    13\\t\\n    14\\t## Intent (what / why)\\n    15\\t\\n    16\\tWednesdayAI agents face a growing skill library (56+ bundled skills, plus user-installed skills) dumped entirely into the system prompt. This burns 5K–15K context tokens just on skill descriptions, 95% of which are irrelevant to any given query. For complex multi-step queries (\\\"download this dataset, analyze it, email the report\\\"), the agent must scan all skills and guess which to compose — there's no routing intelligence.\\n    17\\t\\n    18\\tSkillWeaver (Gao 2026, arXiv:2606.18051) formalizes this as the **Compositional Skill Routing** problem and demonstrates a decompose-retrieve-compose pipeline that:\\n    19\\t- Reduces context window consumption by **>99%** (884K → ~2K tokens at 2,209-skill scale)\\n    20\\t- Improves decomposition accuracy from 51% → 67.7% via Skill-Aware Decomposition (SAD)\\n    21\\t- Achieves Category Recall@10 of ~70% using metadata-only bi-encoder retrieval\\n    22\\t\\n    23\\tThis plugin brings SkillWeaver to WednesdayAI as a community extension, serving dual purpose: a production-grade skill router AND a reference implementation for the `context.collect` hook pattern.\\n    24\\t\\n    25\\t## Users / who is affected\\n    26\\t\\n    27\\t| User | Impact |\\n    28\\t|------|--------|\\n    29\\t| **End users** (agent operators with many skills) | Automatic routing — no manual skill selection. Smaller context = faster responses, lower API cost. |\\n    30\\t| **Plugin developers** | Reference implementation for `context.collect` + prompt contribution pattern. Demonstrates embedding infrastructure in an extension. |\\n    31\\t| **Skill authors** | Skills get used more accurately — router matches skills to query intent rather than relying on LLM scanning a long list. |\\n    32\\t\\n    33\\t### User stories\\n    34\\t\\n    35\\tUS1: As an agent operator, I want skills automatically matched to my query so I don't waste context tokens on irrelevant skill descriptions, and so complex multi-step queries are decomposed and routed correctly.\\n    36\\t\\n    37\\tUS2: As a plugin developer, I want a reference implementation of the `context.collect` hook pattern for skill routing so I can build similar plugins without breaking system prompt caching.\\n    38\\t\\n    39\\tUS3: As an infrastructure operator, I want to choose my embedding backend (local/cloud/custom) so I can optimize for cost, latency, privacy, or existing self-hosted infrastructure.\\n    40\\t\\n    41\\t## Success criteria\\n    42\\t\\n    43\\t### CatR@10 ≥ 65%\\n    44\\tSC1: Retrieval accuracy — On a benchmark of 50 compositional queries against WednesdayAI's bundled skills, CatR@10 ≥ 65% (correct-category skill in top-10 candidates per sub-task). → US1:\\n    45\\t\\n    46\\t### DA ≥ 60%\\n    47\\tSC2: Decomposition accuracy — SAD decomposition produces correct step count (DA) on ≥ 60% of compositional queries (baseline: vanilla LLM decomposition ~45-50%). → US1:\\n    48\\t\\n    49\\t### Context ≤ 300 tokens\\n    50\\tSC3: Context reduction — When active with `skills: \\\"names\\\"` config, the skills section of the system prompt ≤ 300 tokens (vs ~8K–15K in \\\"default\\\" mode). → US1:\\n    51\\t\\n    52\\t### No cache regression\\n    53\\tSC4: Cache safety — System prompt cache hit rate unchanged from baseline (skills injected as conversation context, not system prompt). → US1:\\n    54\\t\\n    55\\t### Slash commands preserved\\n    56\\tSC5: Slash command survival — All existing skill slash commands (`/github`, `/weather`, etc.) continue functioning when plugin is active. → US1: US2:\\n    57\\t\\n    58\\t### 3 embedding backends\\n    59\\tSC6: Pluggable embedding — Plugin works with at least three embedding backends: local (all-MiniLM-L6-v2 via @xenova/transformers), cloud (OpenAI text-embedding-3-small), custom (arbitrary OpenAI-compatible endpoint, e.g. Infinity in Docker). → US1: US3:\\n    60\\t\\n    61\\t### ≤ 5s latency\\n    62\\tSC7: Latency budget — End-to-end routing (decompose + retrieve + inject) adds ≤ 3s overhead to agent startup on typical hardware. Optional SAD decomposition pass adds ≤ 5s. → US1:\\n    63\\t\\n    64\\t## Constraints\\n    65\\t\\n    66\\t- **Extension only** — no core changes to WednesdayAI. Uses existing `context.collect` hook + `api.config`.\\n    67\\t- **Skill index built at startup** — embedding index constructed in `register()`, updated on skill file changes via fs watch (debounced).\\n    68\\t- **Separate decomposer model** — configurable, defaults to agent's own model but should support a cheaper/smaller model (e.g., Qwen2.5-7B, gpt-4o-mini) to reduce the decomposition cost overhead.\\n    69\\t- **No core config mutation** — plugin cannot set `agents.defaults.systemPrompt.sections.skills`. Must detect and warn; user configures manually.\\n    70\\t- **Node.js ≥ 24** — same runtime requirement as WednesdayAI core.\\n    71\\t- **External dependency ceiling** — max 3 new npm deps (embedding lib, vector index, maybe an MCP SDK for skill catalog query).\\n    72\\t\\n    73\\t## Out of scope\\n    74\\t\\n    75\\t- **Compose/DAG planner** (Stage 3 of SkillWeaver) — the paper's compose stage with inter-skill compatibility scoring. V1 focuses on decompose + retrieve; composition is sequential (order from decomposition).\\n    76\\t- **Iterative SAD convergence monitoring** — V1 runs exactly 1 SAD iteration (Pass-1 decompose → retrieve → Pass-2 re-decompose). Multi-iteration with hint Jaccard convergence is V2.\\n    77\\t- **LLM listwise reranker** — the paper's appendix K reranker that lifts CatR@1 +10.3%. V2 or separate plugin.\\n    78\\t- **MCP tool catalog integration** — this plugin routes WednesdayAI *skills* (SKILL.md instructional content), not MCP tools. A separate plugin could handle MCP tool routing using the same pattern.\\n    79\\t- **Runtime skill execution orchestration** — the plugin selects skills; it does not execute them or manage the execution DAG.\\n    80\\t- **Skill usage analytics / telemetry**.\\n    81\\t- **Auto-configuration of `skills: \\\"names\\\"`** — we can't mutate core config. Documentation + startup warning only.\\n    82\\t\\n    83\\t## Approach\\n    84\\t\\n    85\\tThe plugin injects retrieved skill descriptions into the **conversation** (not the system prompt) via the `context.collect` lifecycle hook — the same seam `memory-lancedb` uses for auto-recall. This preserves the system prompt's full cacheability while delivering query-relevant skill content exactly where the agent needs it: alongside the user's message.\\n    86\\t\\n    87\\tPer-agent-run pipeline:\\n    88\\t1. `context.collect` fires with the clean user message\\n    89\\t2. If query length < `minQueryLength` (default 20 chars), skip — simple queries don't need routing\\n    90\\t3. Otherwise: run SAD decomposition (2-pass) against the configured decomposer model\\n    91\\t4. Retrieve top-K skills per sub-task from the embedding index\\n    92\\t5. Return skill descriptions as `prependContext` blocks in a `PromptContribution`\\n    93\\t6. The hook runner injects these blocks into the conversation context before the user message\\n    94\\t\\n    95\\tSkill index lifecycle:\\n    96\\t- Built in `register()` at plugin startup\\n    97\\t- Watched for changes via fs.watch (debounced rebuild)\\n    98\\t- In-memory hnswlib index, never persisted to disk (rebuild is cheap at 56–200 skills)\\n    99\\t\\n   100\\tConfig adaptation:\\n   101\\t- At startup, read `api.config.agents.defaults.systemPrompt.sections.skills`\\n   102\\t- If `\\\"default\\\"` or unset: log a warning recommending `\\\"names\\\"` mode\\n   103\\t- Plugin works regardless — but with redundancy in \\\"default\\\" mode\\n   104\\t\\n   105\\t## Design / architecture\\n   106\\t\\n   107\\t### Components\\n   108\\t\\n   109\\t```\\n   110\\t┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐\\n   111\\t│                  plugin-skillweaver                   │\\n   112\\t├─────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤\\n   113\\t│  register(api)                                       │\\n   114\\t│    ├─ ConfigValidator ── validates plugin config     │\\n   115\\t│    ├─ SkillIndex ──────── builds vector index        │\\n   116\\t│    │   ├─ EmbeddingBackend (local/cloud/custom)      │\\n   117\\t│    │   └─ hnswlib index (in-memory)                  │\\n   118\\t│    ├─ Decomposer ──────── SAD pipeline               │\\n   119\\t│    │   ├─ decomposerModel (configurable LLM)         │\\n   120\\t│    │   └─ SAD prompt templates                       │\\n   121\\t│    ├─ Retriever ───────── NN search per sub-task     │\\n   122\\t│    └─ ContextInjector ─── PromptContribution builder │\\n   123\\t│                                                      │\\n   124\\t│  api.on(\\\"context.collect\\\", handler)                   │\\n   125\\t└──────────────────────┬──────────────────────────────┘\\n   126\\t                       │ PromptContribution\\n   127\\t                       ▼\\n   128\\t              WednesdayAI hook runner\\n   129\\t              → prependContext injected into conversation\\n   130\\t```\\n   131\\t\\n   132\\t### Data flow (per agent run)\\n   133\\t\\n   134\\t```\\n   135\\tcontext.collect event { cleanUserMessage, messages, envelope }\\n   136\\t  │\\n   137\\t  ├─ query.length < minQueryLength? → return {} (skip)\\n   138\\t  │\\n   139\\t  ├─ Pass 1: Decomposer.decompose(query, hints=null)\\n   140\\t  │   └─ LLM call → [\\\"fetch dataset\\\", \\\"analyze data\\\", \\\"generate report\\\"]\\n   141\\t  │\\n   142\\t  ├─ For each sub-task: SkillIndex.search(subTask, topK=hintSize)\\n   143\\t  │   └─ Embed sub-task → hnswlib NN search → [skill1, skill2, ...]\\n   144\\t  │\\n   145\\t  ├─ Build hint set: deduplicate top result per sub-task, take top hintSize unique\\n   146\\t  │\\n   147\\t  ├─ Pass 2 (SAD): Decomposer.decompose(query, hints=hintSet)\\n   148\\t  │   └─ LLM call + hints → [\\\"download CSV from URL\\\", \\\"run statistical analysis\\\", \\\"create chart\\\"]\\n   149\\t  │\\n   150\\t  ├─ For each refined sub-task: SkillIndex.search(subTask, topK=config.topK)\\n   151\\t  │   └─ Return top-K SkillEntry[]\\n   152\\t  │\\n   153\\t  └─ ContextInjector.format(skillEntries)\\n   154\\t     └─ PromptContribution { prependContext: [ContextBlock, ...] }\\n   155\\t```\\n   156\\t\\n   157\\t### Index schema\\n   158\\t\\n   159\\tEach skill is embedded as a single vector from its `name + description` string:\\n   160\\t\\n   161\\t```\\n   162\\tindexKey = skill.name\\n   163\\tdocument  = `${skill.name}: ${skill.description}`\\n   164\\tvector    = embed(document)  // 384-dim (all-MiniLM-L6-v2) or backend-specific\\n   165\\tmetadata  = { name, description, location, category?, source }\\n   166\\t```\\n   167\\t\\n   168\\tThe skill body (full SKILL.md content) is NOT embedded — the paper shows metadata-only retrieval achieves\\n   169\\tCatR@10 of ~70%, sufficient for the top-K retrieval that SAD feeds into decomposition.\\n   170\\t\\n   171\\t### Hook contribution format\\n   172\\t\\n   173\\t```ts\\n   174\\t// Returned from context.collect handler\\n   175\\t{\\n   176\\t  prependContext: [\\n   177\\t    {\\n   178\\t      id: \\\"skillweaver:route\\\",\\n   179\\t      source: \\\"plugin-skillweaver\\\",\\n   180\\t      text: [\\n   181\\t        \\\"## Skill Routing\\\",\\n   182\\t        `For this query, the following skills are recommended:`,\\n   183\\t        \\\"\\\",\\n   184\\t        \\\"### skill-name\\\",\\n   185\\t        \\\"Description of the skill...\\\",\\n   186\\t        `Location: /path/to/skill/SKILL.md`,\\n   187\\t        \\\"\\\",\\n   188\\t        \\\"### another-skill\\\",\\n   189\\t        \\\"Description...\\\",\\n   190\\t      ].join(\\\"\\\\n\\\"),\\n   191\\t      priority: 10,             // lower = earlier in context\\n   192\\t      tokenEstimate: 1200,\\n   193\\t      metadata: {\\n   194\\t        matchedSkills: [\\\"skill-name\\\", \\\"another-skill\\\"],\\n   195\\t        subTasks: [\\\"download CSV\\\", \\\"run analysis\\\"],\\n   196\\t        decomposerModel: \\\"qwen/qwen2.5-7b-instruct\\\",\\n   197\\t      },\\n   198\\t    },\\n   199\\t  ],\\n   200\\t}\\n   201\\t```\\n   202\\t\\n   203\\t### Plugin config schema\\n   204\\t\\n   205\\t```jsonc\\n   206\\t{\\n   207\\t  \\\"plugins\\\": {\\n   208\\t    \\\"skillweaver\\\": {\\n   209\\t      \\\"enabled\\\": true,              // master on/off\\n   210\\t      \\\"decomposer\\\": {\\n   211\\t        \\\"provider\\\": \\\"openrouter\\\",   // or \\\"openai\\\", \\\"anthropic\\\", \\\"openai-compatible\\\"\\n   212\\t        \\\"model\\\": \\\"qwen/qwen2.5-7b-instruct\\\",\\n   213\\t        \\\"apiKey\\\": null,             // null = use agent's provider creds; string = override\\n   214\\t        \\\"baseUrl\\\": null,            // for openai-compatible endpoints\\n   215\\t        \\\"temperature\\\": 0.1,\\n   216\\t        \\\"maxTokens\\\": 256\\n   217\\t      },\\n   218\\t      \\\"embedding\\\": {\\n   219\\t        \\\"backend\\\": \\\"local\\\",         // \\\"local\\\" | \\\"cloud\\\" | \\\"custom\\\"\\n   220\\t        \\\"model\\\": \\\"all-MiniLM-L6-v2\\\", // local model name (Xenova)\\n   221\\t        \\\"cloudModel\\\": \\\"text-embedding-3-small\\\", // cloud model (OpenAI)\\n   222\\t        \\\"endpoint\\\": null,           // custom: OpenAI-compatible endpoint URL + API key\\n   223\\t        \\\"apiKey\\\": null\\n   224\\t      },\\n   225\\t      \\\"retrieval\\\": {\\n   226\\t        \\\"topK\\\": 3,                  // skills returned per sub-task\\n   227\\t        \\\"hintSize\\\": 15,             // total hints passed to SAD Pass-2\\n   228\\t        \\\"minQueryLength\\\": 20        // skip routing for very short queries\\n   229\\t      },\\n   230\\t      \\\"sad\\\": {\\n   231\\t        \\\"enabled\\\": true,            // enable SAD (2-pass); false = Pass-1 only\\n   232\\t        \\\"maxIterations\\\": 1          // V1 cap; future: multi-iteration\\n   233\\t      }\\n   234\\t    }\\n   235\\t  }\\n   236\\t}\\n   237\\t```\\n   238\\t\\n   239\\t### Embedding backend interface\\n   240\\t\\n   241\\t```ts\\n   242\\tinterface EmbeddingBackend {\\n   243\\t  readonly id: string;\\n   244\\t  readonly dimensions: number;\\n   245\\t  embed(texts: string[]): Promise<Float32Array[]>;\\n   246\\t  embedSingle(text: string): Promise<Float32Array>;\\n   247\\t  dispose(): void | Promise<void>;\\n   248\\t}\\n   249\\t```\\n   250\\t\\n   251\\tThree implementations:\\n   252\\t- `LocalEmbedding` — @xenova/transformers with all-MiniLM-L6-v2 (80MB, runs in-process)\\n   253\\t- `CloudEmbedding` — OpenAI embeddings API (text-embedding-3-small or user-specified)\\n   254\\t- `CustomEmbedding` — any OpenAI-compatible `/v1/embeddings` endpoint (Infinity, Ollama, etc.)\\n   255\\t\\n   256\\tBackend selection happens at `register()` time based on config. The index builder is backend-agnostic.\\n   257\\t\\n   258\\t## Decisions\\n   259\\t\\n   260\\t### D1 — `context.collect` hook for injection (irreversible: contract)\\n   261\\t\\n   262\\t**Choice:** Use `context.collect` hook to inject skill descriptions, not `before_prompt_build`.\\n   263\\t\\n   264\\t**Rationale:** `context.collect` returns `PromptContribution` with `prependContext` blocks, which land in the conversation portion — not the system prompt. This preserves the system prompt cache (Anthropic ephemeral, OpenAI `prompt_cache_key`). `before_prompt_build` returns a `systemPrompt` string that replaces the entire system prompt, which would vary per-query and destroy the cache hit for the full ~15K token system message.\\n   265\\t\\n   266\\t**Trade-off:** Skill content lives in conversation context rather than system instructions, so the agent sees it as \\\"context provided for this turn\\\" rather than \\\"persistent instructions.\\\" This is acceptable — skills are turn-relevant and the \\\"names\\\" config preserves the persistent skill inventory.\\n   267\\t\\n   268\\t**ADR:** [ADR-0001](/dev-docs/adr/0001-context-collect-hook-for-skill-injection.md)\\n   269\\t\\n   270\\t### D2 — Pluggable embedding backend (irreversible: interface contract)\\n   271\\t\\n   272\\t**Choice:** Abstract embedding behind a `EmbeddingBackend` interface with three implementations (local, cloud, custom).\\n   273\\t\\n   274\\t**Rationale:** Users have diverse infrastructure. Some run everything locally (no API keys), some use cloud providers, some self-host embeddings via Infinity/Ollama in Docker. The interface is a thin abstraction — `embed(strings) → vectors` — that any backend can satisfy. The paper uses all-MiniLM-L6-v2 (384-dim), but higher-dimensional models (text-embedding-3-small: 1536-dim) may improve retrieval. The hnswlib index is dimension-agnostic.\\n   275\\t\\n   276\\t**ADR:** [ADR-0002](/dev-docs/adr/0002-pluggable-embedding-backend-interface.md)\\n   277\\t\\n   278\\t### D3 — SAD prompt contract (irreversible: decomposer protocol)\\n   279\\t\\n   280\\t**Choice:** Structured JSON prompt with explicit sub-task format. Pass-1 prompt asks the decomposer to break the query into atomic sub-tasks. Pass-2 prompt adds a `hints` section listing available skill names and descriptions, instructing the model to align sub-task descriptions to the hint vocabulary.\\n   281\\t\\n   282\\t**Rationale:** The paper's key finding: decomposition vocabulary mismatch is the primary bottleneck (36% of failures are over-decomposition, 22% vocabulary mismatch). The SAD prompt must bridge generic LLM descriptions (\\\"download the data\\\") to retrievable skill names (\\\"api-client\\\", \\\"http-fetch\\\"). The hint set provides this vocabulary bridge.\\n   283\\t\\n   284\\tThe prompt contract is: `{ subTasks: string[] }` — a JSON array of one-skill-per-task strings. This is intentionally minimal to keep parsing deterministic.\\n   285\\t\\n   286\\t**ADR:** [ADR-0003](/dev-docs/adr/0003-sad-prompt-contract.md)\\n   287\\t\\n   288\\t### D4 — Metadata-only embedding\\n   289\\t\\n   290\\t**Choice:** Embed only `name + description`, not the full SKILL.md body.\\n   291\\t\\n   292\\t**Rationale:** The paper shows metadata-only retrieval achieves CatR@10 of 69.0% (vs 70.3% with body-aware, a 1.3pp difference). The 99% context reduction already achieved by not dumping full bodies into the prompt. Embedding full bodies would inflate the index size and embedding cost with negligible accuracy gain for the retrieve-then-rerank pipeline.\\n   293\\t\\n   294\\t### D5 — In-memory hnswlib, no persistence\\n   295\\t\\n   296\\t**Choice:** Build the skill index in-memory at startup; never persist to disk. Rebuild on any skill file change.\\n   297\\t\\n   298\\t**Rationale:** 56–200 skills × 384-dim vectors = negligible memory (<1MB). Rebuild takes <1s. Adding persistence (file I/O, serialization format, invalidation rules, format versioning) adds complexity with no practical benefit at this scale. If the plugin ecosystem grows to thousands of skills, persistence can be added later behind the same `SkillIndex` interface.\\n   299\\t\\n   300\\t**ADR:** [ADR-0004](/dev-docs/adr/0004-in-memory-index-no-persistence.md)\\n   301\\t\\n   302\\t### D6 — Separate decomposer model, configurable\\n   303\\t\\n   304\\t**Choice:** The decomposition LLM call uses a separately configurable model, not the agent's primary model.\\n   305\\t\\n   306\\t**Rationale:** Decomposition needs a model that follows structured instructions precisely (structured JSON output), not a model that's creative or conversational. A smaller, cheaper model (Qwen2.5-7B, gpt-4o-mini) does this well. This also avoids consuming the agent's rate limits and context window for the routing pass. Users can configure the decomposer model independently of their agent model, including using a different provider.\\n   307\\t\\n   308\\t## Test strategy\\n   309\\t\\n   310\\t### Unit tests\\n   311\\t\\n   312\\t| Module | What's tested |\\n   313\\t|--------|--------------|\\n   314\\t| `SkillIndex` | Build from skill entries, search returns correct results, rebuild on fs change, empty library, deduplicated names |\\n   315\\t| `Decomposer` | Parse valid JSON response, handle malformed JSON, handle empty/missing subTasks field, Pass-1 no hints, Pass-2 with hints |\\n   316\\t| `Retriever` | Cosine similarity ranking, top-K truncation, dedup across sub-tasks, score threshold filtering |\\n   317\\t| `ContextInjector` | Format skill entries → PromptContribution, empty results → empty contribution, token count estimation |\\n   318\\t| `ConfigValidator` | Valid config passes, missing required fields, invalid backend names, invalid model names |\\n   319\\t| `EmbeddingBackend` (×3) | Local: loads model, embeds text, correct dimensions. Cloud: sends correct API request format. Custom: handles endpoint URL and auth. |\\n   320\\t\\n   321\\t### Integration tests\\n   322\\t\\n   323\\t| Scenario | Verification |\\n   324\\t|----------|-------------|\\n   325\\t| Full pipeline (mock LLM) | Query → decompose → retrieve → inject → correct PromptContribution shape |\\n   326\\t| All 3 embedding backends | Same skill set, same query, results within tolerance across backends |\\n   327\\t| Hook registration | `context.collect` handler registered on `api.on()`, fires on agent run |\\n   328\\t| Config adaptation warning | \\\"default\\\" skills mode → warning logged. \\\"names\\\"/\\\"off\\\" → no warning |\\n   329\\t| Cache boundary | Skill content lands in `prependContext` (conversation), not `systemPrompt` |\\n   330\\t| Slash commands | Verify skill commands still resolve when plugin active |\\n   331\\t| Sub-agent propagation | Plugin does NOT fire for sub-agents (check `envelope` for sub-agent flag) |\\n   332\\t| Error resilience | Embedding backend down → gracefully skip routing, don't crash agent run |\\n   333\\t| Short query skip | Query ≤ `minQueryLength` → no routing, no decomposer call |\\n   334\\t\\n   335\\t### Benchmark suite\\n   336\\t\\n   337\\t50 compositional queries derived from WednesdayAI's bundled skill categories:\\n   338\\t- 25 \\\"easy\\\" (2 skills, 2 categories)\\n   339\\t- 15 \\\"medium\\\" (3 skills, 3 categories)\\n   340\\t- 10 \\\"hard\\\" (4–5 skills, 4–5 categories)\\n   341\\t\\n   342\\tMeasured: CatR@10, CatR@1, DA, DA±1, latency (decompose + retrieve).\\n   343\\tCompared: Vanilla (Pass-1 only, no hints) vs SAD (2-pass with hints).\\n   344\\t\\n   345\\t### Edge case tests\\n   346\\t\\n   347\\t- Empty skill library → index builds with 0 entries, search returns []\\n   348\\t- Skill with empty description → still indexed by name\\n   349\\t- Decomposer returns 0 sub-tasks → skip retrieval, return empty contribution\\n   350\\t- Decomposer returns 20 sub-tasks → cap at configurable max (default 10)\\n   351\\t- User message is a single word (\\\"hi\\\", \\\"thanks\\\") → skip routing\\n   352\\t- User message is a URL → skip routing (not a compositional query)\\n   353\\t- Embedding backend times out → catch, log, return empty contribution (never crash)\\n   354\\t- Two skills with identical names from different sources → last-loaded wins, log warning\\n   355\\t- Plugin uninstalled while index is building → clean teardown\",\"exit_code\":0,\"status\":\"completed\"}}\ndocs/plans/plugin-skillweaver/reviews/tournament-r1-codex.raw.log:27:{\"type\":\"item.started\",\"item\":{\"id\":\"item_14\",\"type\":\"command_execution\",\"command\":\"/bin/zsh -lc 'for f in dev-docs/adr/0001-context-collect-hook-for-skill-injection.md dev-docs/adr/0002-pluggable-embedding-backend-interface.md dev-docs/adr/0003-sad-prompt-contract.md dev-docs/adr/0004-in-memory-index-no-persistence.md; do nl -ba \\\"$f\\\"; done'\",\"aggregated_output\":\"\",\"exit_code\":null,\"status\":\"in_progress\"}}\ndocs/plans/plugin-skillweaver/reviews/tournament-r1-codex.raw.log:28:{\"type\":\"item.completed\",\"item\":{\"id\":\"item_14\",\"type\":\"command_execution\",\"command\":\"/bin/zsh -lc 'for f in dev-docs/adr/0001-context-collect-hook-for-skill-injection.md dev-docs/adr/0002-pluggable-embedding-backend-interface.md dev-docs/adr/0003-sad-prompt-contract.md dev-docs/adr/0004-in-memory-index-no-persistence.md; do nl -ba \\\"$f\\\"; done'\",\"aggregated_output\":\"     1\\t---\\n     2\\tdoc_type: adr\\n     3\\tid: 0001\\n     4\\tworkstream: plugin-skillweaver\\n     5\\ttitle: \\\"ADR-0001: Use context.collect hook for skill injection\\\"\\n     6\\tstatus: accepted\\n     7\\tcreated: 2026-07-06\\n     8\\t---\\n     9\\t\\n    10\\t# ADR-0001: Use `context.collect` hook for skill injection\\n    11\\t\\n    12\\t## Context\\n    13\\t\\n    14\\tThe SkillWeaver plugin must inject retrieved skill descriptions into the agent's context on each run. WednesdayAI provides two candidate hooks:\\n    15\\t\\n    16\\t1. **`before_prompt_build`** — returns a `systemPrompt` string that *replaces* the entire system prompt. Can also return `prependContext`.\\n    17\\t\\n    18\\t2. **`context.collect`** — returns a `PromptContribution` with `prependContext`, `appendContext`, `appendAfterUserMessage`, and other blocks that land in the *conversation* portion, not the system prompt.\\n    19\\t\\n    20\\t## Decision\\n    21\\t\\n    22\\tUse `context.collect` hook for skill injection. Do not use `before_prompt_build`.\\n    23\\t\\n    24\\t## Rationale\\n    25\\t\\n    26\\t### Cache preservation\\n    27\\t\\n    28\\tWednesdayAI's system prompt is fully cached via:\\n    29\\t- Anthropic: `cache_control: { type: \\\"ephemeral\\\" }` on the system message\\n    30\\t- OpenAI: `prompt_cache_key` keyed on `agent+model` (not conversation)\\n    31\\t\\n    32\\tIf we inject per-query skill content into the system prompt (via `before_prompt_build`'s `systemPrompt` return), the system prompt varies per request → cache miss → full ~15K token cost instead of ~1.5K (cached read at 10%).\\n    33\\t\\n    34\\tIf we inject skill content into the conversation (via `context.collect`'s `prependContext`), the system prompt stays identical across requests → full cache hit. The conversation portion is dynamic anyway — adding 500–1500 tokens of skill descriptions has zero marginal caching penalty.\\n    35\\t\\n    36\\t### Correct semantic placement\\n    37\\t\\n    38\\tSkill routing is a *per-query* concern. The skills relevant to \\\"analyze this CSV\\\" are different from those for \\\"deploy this Docker container.\\\" Placing skill descriptions in the system prompt (persistent, session-scoped instructions) implies they're always relevant — they're not. Placing them in the conversation context (\\\"here are skills for *this specific query*\\\") is semantically correct.\\n    39\\t\\n    40\\t### Proven pattern\\n    41\\t\\n    42\\tThe `memory-lancedb` extension already uses this pattern: it reads the user message, searches a vector DB for relevant memories, and injects them as `prependContext` via `context.collect`. SkillWeaver follows the same architecture: search → inject as conversation context.\\n    43\\t\\n    44\\t## Consequences\\n    45\\t\\n    46\\t- **Positive:** Full system prompt cache preservation. No cache regression from enabling the plugin.\\n    47\\t- **Positive:** Skill descriptions appear in the conversation at the right time (before the user message) and are naturally pruned by compaction like any other context.\\n    48\\t- **Negative:** Skill content is not in the system prompt, so it's not \\\"permanent instructions.\\\" The `skills: \\\"names\\\"` config preserves a lightweight index in the system prompt to compensate.\\n    49\\t- **Negative:** The `context.collect` hook does not receive the final assembled system prompt — we can't inspect whether the user actually has `skills: \\\"names\\\"` set at runtime. We must check `api.config` at startup instead.\\n    50\\t\\n    51\\t## Alternatives considered\\n    52\\t\\n    53\\t### `before_prompt_build` with `prependContext`\\n    54\\tThis returns `prependContext` (not `systemPrompt`), which also lands in conversation. But the hook signature bundles `systemPrompt` override capability, creating a footgun risk (future maintainer uses `systemPrompt` return, breaks caching). `context.collect` has no `systemPrompt` return — it's impossible to accidentally break caching.\\n    55\\t\\n    56\\t### `context.project` with message rewriting\\n    57\\tCan rewrite the messages array to strip/replace skill descriptions. Too fragile — depends on exact system prompt formatting. Better to not put skill content there in the first place.\\n    58\\t\\n    59\\t### New core hook\\n    60\\tWould require core changes, defeating the \\\"extension-only\\\" constraint. The existing hooks are sufficient.     1\\t---\\n     2\\tdoc_type: adr\\n     3\\tid: 0002\\n     4\\tworkstream: plugin-skillweaver\\n     5\\ttitle: \\\"ADR-0002: Pluggable embedding backend interface\\\"\\n     6\\tstatus: accepted\\n     7\\tcreated: 2026-07-06\\n     8\\t---\\n     9\\t\\n    10\\t# ADR-0002: Pluggable embedding backend interface\\n    11\\t\\n    12\\t## Context\\n    13\\t\\n    14\\tThe SkillWeaver plugin needs to embed skill names and descriptions into vectors for similarity search. Users have diverse embedding infrastructure:\\n    15\\t\\n    16\\t- Some run everything locally (no API keys, air-gapped)\\n    17\\t- Some use cloud providers (OpenAI, Gemini)\\n    18\\t- Some self-host embeddings via Infinity, Ollama, or similar Docker services\\n    19\\t\\n    20\\t## Decision\\n    21\\t\\n    22\\tDefine an `EmbeddingBackend` interface with three concrete implementations selected by config. The interface is:\\n    23\\t\\n    24\\t```ts\\n    25\\tinterface EmbeddingBackend {\\n    26\\t  readonly id: string;\\n    27\\t  readonly dimensions: number;\\n    28\\t  embed(texts: string[]): Promise<Float32Array[]>;\\n    29\\t  embedSingle(text: string): Promise<Float32Array>;\\n    30\\t  dispose(): void | Promise<void>;\\n    31\\t}\\n    32\\t```\\n    33\\t\\n    34\\tThree backends:\\n    35\\t1. **`local`** — `@xenova/transformers` with `all-MiniLM-L6-v2` (384-dim). Runs in-process, no network, 80MB model download on first use.\\n    36\\t2. **`cloud`** — OpenAI `/v1/embeddings` API. Defaults to `text-embedding-3-small` (1536-dim). Requires API key.\\n    37\\t3. **`custom`** — Any OpenAI-compatible `/v1/embeddings` endpoint. User provides URL, model name, optional API key.\\n    38\\t\\n    39\\t## Rationale\\n    40\\t\\n    41\\t### Interface is intentionally minimal\\n    42\\t\\n    43\\tTwo methods: `embed` (batch) and `embedSingle` (convenience). No streaming, no fine-tuning, no model management. This keeps the contract simple enough that all three backends are trivial to implement. The index layer doesn't care which backend it uses — it just calls `embed()`.\\n    44\\t\\n    45\\t### Dimension-agnostic index\\n    46\\t\\n    47\\tThe hnswlib index is dimension-agnostic — it stores vectors of whatever dimension the backend produces. This means switching from local (384-dim) to cloud (1536-dim) requires a full index rebuild (re-embed all skills), but no code changes. Config change + restart = new backend active.\\n    48\\t\\n    49\\t### Local as default, cloud as upgrade\\n    50\\t\\n    51\\tThe default is local (`all-MiniLM-L6-v2`) because it requires zero configuration — no API keys, no endpoints, no network. It works immediately. The paper validates this exact model. Users who want higher accuracy can switch to cloud (OpenAI `text-embedding-3-small`) which has a better embedding quality at the cost of API latency + cost.\\n    52\\t\\n    53\\t### Custom for self-hosters\\n    54\\t\\n    55\\tUsers running Infinity, Ollama, or other OpenAI-compatible embedding servers can point the plugin at their local endpoint. No new code path — just a different URL. This covers the \\\"Infinity in Docker with all-MiniLM-L6-v2\\\" use case without adding Infinity-specific code.\\n    56\\t\\n    57\\t## Consequences\\n    58\\t\\n    59\\t- **Positive:** Users choose their own cost/latency/privacy trade-off.\\n    60\\t- **Positive:** Interface is small enough that adding a 4th backend (e.g., Gemini embedding, Cohere) is a single file.\\n    61\\t- **Negative:** Different backends produce different-quality embeddings for the same text. The benchmark suite must validate all three backends independently.\\n    62\\t- **Negative:** Switching backends requires a full index rebuild (embed all skills from scratch). Acceptable because skill count is small (56–200) and rebuild is <1s.\\n    63\\t\\n    64\\t## Alternatives considered\\n    65\\t\\n    66\\t### Single backend (local only)\\n    67\\tSimpler, but excludes users who prefer cloud embeddings or self-host embedding servers. Rejected — the paper itself uses cloud embeddings for some experiments; local-only is unnecessarily restrictive.\\n    68\\t\\n    69\\t### Multiple backends with auto-fallback\\n    70\\t\\\"Try cloud, fall back to local if unavailable.\\\" Adds complexity (retry logic, degraded-accuracy mode) with unclear benefit. If the user picks a backend, they expect it to be used. Explicit config > magic fallback.\\n    71\\t\\n    72\\t### Transformer.js model selection within local backend\\n    73\\tAllow any Xenova model, not just all-MiniLM-L6-v2. Rejected for V1 — model dimension must be known at index creation time, and supporting arbitrary models adds config validation complexity. The custom backend already handles \\\"any model I want\\\" via the OpenAI-compatible endpoint path.     1\\t---\\n     2\\tdoc_type: adr\\n     3\\tid: 0003\\n     4\\tworkstream: plugin-skillweaver\\n     5\\ttitle: \\\"ADR-0003: SAD prompt contract and response format\\\"\\n     6\\tstatus: accepted\\n     7\\tcreated: 2026-07-06\\n     8\\t---\\n     9\\t\\n    10\\t# ADR-0003: SAD prompt contract and response format\\n    11\\t\\n    12\\t## Context\\n    13\\t\\n    14\\tThe Skill-Aware Decomposition (SAD) pipeline sends two prompts to the decomposer LLM:\\n    15\\t\\n    16\\t1. **Pass 1** — decompose the query into atomic sub-tasks with no skill hints\\n    17\\t2. **Pass 2** — re-decompose with a hint set of skill names and descriptions from Pass-1 retrieval\\n    18\\t\\n    19\\tThe prompt format and response parsing are a contract between the plugin and any decomposer model. If this format changes, decomposition quality may degrade until the new prompt is tuned.\\n    20\\t\\n    21\\t## Decision\\n    22\\t\\n    23\\t### Pass 1 prompt (vanilla decomposition)\\n    24\\t\\n    25\\t```\\n    26\\tSystem: You are a task decomposer. Break complex user queries into atomic sub-tasks.\\n    27\\tEach sub-task should require exactly one skill or tool to complete.\\n    28\\tOutput a JSON object with a \\\"subTasks\\\" array of strings.\\n    29\\tDo not include any other text.\\n    30\\t\\n    31\\tUser: <query>\\n    32\\t\\n    33\\tOutput format: { \\\"subTasks\\\": [\\\"task 1\\\", \\\"task 2\\\", ...] }\\n    34\\t```\\n    35\\t\\n    36\\t### Pass 2 prompt (SAD with hints)\\n    37\\t\\n    38\\tSame system prompt, but the user message is extended:\\n    39\\t\\n    40\\t```\\n    41\\tUser: <query>\\n    42\\t\\n    43\\tAvailable skills (use these names where applicable):\\n    44\\t- skill-name: description of what the skill does\\n    45\\t- another-skill: another description\\n    46\\t...\\n    47\\t\\n    48\\tAlign your sub-task descriptions to match the available skill vocabulary.\\n    49\\tOutput format: { \\\"subTasks\\\": [\\\"task 1\\\", \\\"task 2\\\", ...] }\\n    50\\t```\\n    51\\t\\n    52\\t### Response format\\n    53\\t\\n    54\\t```json\\n    55\\t{ \\\"subTasks\\\": [\\\"string\\\", \\\"string\\\", ...] }\\n    56\\t```\\n    57\\t\\n    58\\tParsing: extract first JSON object from response → validate `subTasks` is an array of strings → max 10 sub-tasks → truncate if exceeded.\\n    59\\t\\n    60\\t### Hint construction\\n    61\\t\\n    62\\tFrom Pass-1 retrieval results across all sub-tasks:\\n    63\\t1. Take the top-1 result per sub-task (most relevant skill per sub-task)\\n    64\\t2. Deduplicate by skill name\\n    65\\t3. Take the top `hintSize` (default 15) entries ranked by retrieval score\\n    66\\t4. Format each hint as: `- skill-name: description`\\n    67\\t5. If hints < 3 (very poor retrieval), include a generic fallback: \\\"If no skill matches, describe the task in general terms.\\\"\\n    68\\t\\n    69\\t## Rationale\\n    70\\t\\n    71\\t### JSON-only, no markdown wrapping\\n    72\\t\\n    73\\tThe decomposer must output pure JSON. Markdown code fences (` ```json ... ``` `) are stripped before parsing. This avoids the most common parsing failure mode (model wraps JSON in markdown). Any JSON object in the response is matched by regex — the first valid `{...}` wins.\\n    74\\t\\n    75\\t### Hint format: name + description, not raw JSON\\n    76\\t\\n    77\\tHints are formatted as human-readable bullet points, not a JSON array of skill objects. Rationale: the decomposer LLM is better at reading natural language than parsing nested JSON structures in a prompt. The format `- name: description` is compact (15 hints × ~75 chars = ~1,100 tokens) and readable.\\n    78\\t\\n    79\\t### Max 10 sub-tasks\\n    80\\t\\n    81\\tThe paper's benchmark has queries with up to 5 ground-truth sub-tasks. Capping at 10 prevents runaway decomposition on simple queries while allowing reasonable headroom. The cap is configurable but defaults to 10.\\n    82\\t\\n    83\\t### Fallback on poor retrieval\\n    84\\t\\n    85\\tIf Pass-1 retrieves <3 distinct skills (very poor retrieval, possibly for a query about a domain with no matching skills), the hint set includes a generic fallback sentence. This prevents the decomposer from hallucinating skill names that don't exist — it instructs the model to use generic descriptions instead.\\n    86\\t\\n    87\\t### Single-iteration in V1\\n    88\\t\\n    89\\tThe paper shows DA converges after iteration 1 (51.3% → 67.0%), with CatR@1 peaking at iteration 2 (38.9%). V1 runs one iteration. Multi-iteration with Jaccard convergence monitoring is V2 scope.\\n    90\\t\\n    91\\t## Consequences\\n    92\\t\\n    93\\t- **Positive:** Structured, deterministic parsing. Any model that can output JSON works.\\n    94\\t- **Positive:** Hint format is compact and human-readable — doesn't require the decomposer to parse a complex data structure.\\n    95\\t- **Positive:** Fallback on poor retrieval prevents hallucination.\\n    96\\t- **Negative:** Prompt quality directly impacts decomposition accuracy. Different decomposer models may need different prompt tuning. The benchmark suite should validate with 2–3 different decomposer models.\\n    97\\t- **Negative:** JSON parsing is fragile — a model that adds explanatory text before/after the JSON object may cause parse failures. The regex extraction (`/{[\\\\s\\\\S]*}/`) mitigates this but isn't perfect.\\n    98\\t\\n    99\\t## Alternatives considered\\n   100\\t\\n   101\\t### Function/tool calling for decomposition\\n   102\\tRegister a `decompose_query` tool and let the model call it. More robust parsing (the model outputs a tool call, not raw JSON). Rejected because: (1) adds complexity — we'd need to construct a full tool-calling message, (2) not all small/cheap models support tool calling well, (3) the prompt-based approach is simpler and the paper validates it.\\n   103\\t\\n   104\\t### XML/structured text instead of JSON\\n   105\\tSome models (Claude) handle XML better than JSON in prompts. Rejected for V1 — JSON is universally supported and simpler to parse. If Claude models consistently fail JSON output, an XML variant can be added behind the same `Decomposer` interface.\\n   106\\t\\n   107\\t### Embedding the hints directly (no Pass-2 prompt)\\n   108\\tInstead of feeding hints back to the decomposer LLM, embed the hint set into the retrieval index and re-retrieve. Rejected — the paper shows SAD's gains come from the LLM aligning its vocabulary to the hint set, not from better retrieval. Retrieval-only feedback doesn't fix over-decomposition (36% of failures).     1\\t---\\n     2\\tdoc_type: adr\\n     3\\tid: 0004\\n     4\\tworkstream: plugin-skillweaver\\n     5\\ttitle: \\\"ADR-0004: In-memory skill index, no persistence\\\"\\n     6\\tstatus: accepted\\n     7\\tcreated: 2026-07-06\\n     8\\t---\\n     9\\t\\n    10\\t# ADR-0004: In-memory skill index, no persistence\\n    11\\t\\n    12\\t## Context\\n    13\\t\\n    14\\tThe SkillWeaver plugin builds a vector index of all skill `name + description` strings at startup. We must decide whether to persist this index to disk or rebuild it in-memory on every startup.\\n    15\\t\\n    16\\t## Decision\\n    17\\t\\n    18\\tBuild the skill index in-memory at plugin startup. Do not persist to disk. Rebuild on any skill file change (fs.watch, debounced).\\n    19\\t\\n    20\\t## Rationale\\n    21\\t\\n    22\\tAt WednesdayAI's current skill scale (56 bundled + up to ~150 user-installed = ~200 skills), the index is trivial:\\n    23\\t\\n    24\\t- 200 skills × 384-dim vectors = **307KB** of vector data\\n    25\\t- 200 skills × ~200 bytes metadata = **~40KB** of metadata\\n    26\\t- Total index footprint: **<1MB memory**\\n    27\\t- Build time: embed 200 texts × local all-MiniLM-L6-v2 ≈ **<500ms**\\n    28\\t- Cloud backend: 200 texts × ~50ms/embed ≈ **~10s** (one-time)\\n    29\\t\\n    30\\tAdding persistence would require:\\n    31\\t- Serialization format (binary, JSON, or msgpack)\\n    32\\t- File I/O with atomic writes\\n    33\\t- Invalidation rules (checksum mismatch, model change, skill file change)\\n    34\\t- Migration strategy for format changes\\n    35\\t- Version tracking to detect stale caches\\n    36\\t\\n    37\\tThis complexity has **zero practical benefit** at current scale. The rebuild cost (<1s local, ~10s cloud) is paid once at gateway startup or plugin reload — it's not on the critical path for any agent request.\\n    38\\t\\n    39\\tIf the WednesdayAI skill ecosystem grows to thousands of skills (matching CompSkillBench's 2,209-skill pool), persistence can be added later behind the same `SkillIndex` interface without changing any consumer code.\\n    40\\t\\n    41\\t## Consequences\\n    42\\t\\n    43\\t- **Positive:** Simpler code — no serialization, no file I/O, no invalidation, no migration.\\n    44\\t- **Positive:** Always fresh — index is rebuilt from current skill files on every startup. No stale cache bugs.\\n    45\\t- **Positive:** Dimension-agnostic — if the user switches embedding backends (384-dim → 1536-dim), the index rebuilds automatically with the new dimensions. A persisted index would need dimension-aware invalidation.\\n    46\\t- **Negative:** ~500ms–10s startup latency while index builds. Paid once at gateway start / plugin load, not per-request. Acceptable.\\n    47\\t- **Negative:** Cloud embedding backends pay API cost on every rebuild. At 200 skills × $0.02/1K tokens (OpenAI ada-002 pricing), rebuild costs ~$0.002. Negligible.\\n    48\\t\\n    49\\t## Alternatives considered\\n    50\\t\\n    51\\t### Persist to ~/.openclaw/skillweaver/index.bin\\n    52\\tSave and load the hnswlib index state. Rejected — complexity > benefit at current scale. Revisit when skill count exceeds ~1,000.\\n    53\\t\\n    54\\t### Persist embeddings only, rebuild index from cached embeddings\\n    55\\tStore the embedding vectors as JSON, rebuild hnswlib index from them on load. Similar complexity to full persistence. Rejected for same reason.\\n    56\\t\\n    57\\t### SQLite with sqlite-vec extension\\n    58\\tUse SQLite's vector extension for storage + query. Would solve persistence naturally, but adds a native dependency and schema management. Overkill for <1MB index.\",\"exit_code\":0,\"status\":\"completed\"}}\ndocs/plans/plugin-skillweaver/reviews/tournament-r1-codex.raw.log:32:{\"type\":\"item.completed\",\"item\":{\"id\":\"item_15\",\"type\":\"command_execution\",\"command\":\"/bin/zsh -lc 'nl -ba docs/plans/plugin-skillweaver/phase-1/001-plugin-scaffold.md && nl -ba docs/plans/plugin-skillweaver/phase-1/002-config-schema.md && nl -ba docs/plans/plugin-skillweaver/phase-1/003-register-entry.md'\",\"aggregated_output\":\"     1\\t---\\n     2\\tid: \\\"001\\\"\\n     3\\tphase: 1\\n     4\\ttitle: Create extension package scaffolding (package.json, openclaw.plugin.json, tsconfig.json)\\n     5\\tstatus: ready\\n     6\\tdepends_on: []\\n     7\\tparallel: false\\n     8\\tconflicts_with: []\\n     9\\tfiles:\\n    10\\t  - extensions/skillweaver/package.json\\n    11\\t  - extensions/skillweaver/openclaw.plugin.json\\n    12\\t  - extensions/skillweaver/tsconfig.json\\n    13\\tirreversible: false\\n    14\\tscope_test: \\\"extensions/skillweaver\\\"\\n    15\\tallowed_change: create\\n    16\\tcovers_criteria: []\\n    17\\t---\\n    18\\t## Failing test (write first)\\n    19\\t\\n    20\\tCreate `extensions/skillweaver/package.test.ts`:\\n    21\\t\\n    22\\t```ts\\n    23\\timport { describe, it, expect } from \\\"vitest\\\";\\n    24\\timport { existsSync, readFileSync } from \\\"node:fs\\\";\\n    25\\timport path from \\\"node:path\\\";\\n    26\\t\\n    27\\tconst root = path.resolve(import.meta.dirname!);\\n    28\\t\\n    29\\tdescribe(\\\"extension package scaffolding\\\", () => {\\n    30\\t  it(\\\"package.json exists and is valid JSON\\\", () => {\\n    31\\t    const pkgPath = path.join(root, \\\"package.json\\\");\\n    32\\t    expect(existsSync(pkgPath)).toBe(true);\\n    33\\t    const pkg = JSON.parse(readFileSync(pkgPath, \\\"utf-8\\\"));\\n    34\\t    expect(pkg.name).toBe(\\\"@wednesdayai/skillweaver\\\");\\n    35\\t    expect(pkg.type).toBe(\\\"module\\\");\\n    36\\t    expect(pkg.openclaw).toBeDefined();\\n    37\\t    expect(pkg.openclaw.extensions).toEqual([\\\"./index.ts\\\"]);\\n    38\\t  });\\n    39\\t\\n    40\\t  it(\\\"openclaw.plugin.json exists with required manifest fields\\\", () => {\\n    41\\t    const manifestPath = path.join(root, \\\"openclaw.plugin.json\\\");\\n    42\\t    expect(existsSync(manifestPath)).toBe(true);\\n    43\\t    const manifest = JSON.parse(readFileSync(manifestPath, \\\"utf-8\\\"));\\n    44\\t    expect(manifest.id).toBe(\\\"skillweaver\\\");\\n    45\\t    expect(manifest.configSchema).toBeDefined();\\n    46\\t  });\\n    47\\t\\n    48\\t  it(\\\"tsconfig.json exists and targets ESM\\\", () => {\\n    49\\t    const tsconfigPath = path.join(root, \\\"tsconfig.json\\\");\\n    50\\t    expect(existsSync(tsconfigPath)).toBe(true);\\n    51\\t    const tsconfig = JSON.parse(readFileSync(tsconfigPath, \\\"utf-8\\\"));\\n    52\\t    expect(tsconfig.compilerOptions.module).toBe(\\\"NodeNext\\\");\\n    53\\t    expect(tsconfig.compilerOptions.moduleResolution).toBe(\\\"NodeNext\\\");\\n    54\\t  });\\n    55\\t});\\n    56\\t```\\n    57\\t\\n    58\\t## Change\\n    59\\t\\n    60\\tFor each file in `files:`:\\n    61\\t\\n    62\\t**File:** `extensions/skillweaver/package.json`\\n    63\\t**Anchor:** new file — create at this path\\n    64\\t**Before:** file does not exist\\n    65\\t**After:**\\n    66\\t```json\\n    67\\t{\\n    68\\t  \\\"name\\\": \\\"@wednesdayai/skillweaver\\\",\\n    69\\t  \\\"version\\\": \\\"0.1.0\\\",\\n    70\\t  \\\"private\\\": true,\\n    71\\t  \\\"description\\\": \\\"SkillWeaver — compositional skill routing for WednesdayAI via context.collect hook\\\",\\n    72\\t  \\\"type\\\": \\\"module\\\",\\n    73\\t  \\\"main\\\": \\\"./index.ts\\\",\\n    74\\t  \\\"scripts\\\": {\\n    75\\t    \\\"test\\\": \\\"vitest run\\\",\\n    76\\t    \\\"test:watch\\\": \\\"vitest\\\"\\n    77\\t  },\\n    78\\t  \\\"dependencies\\\": {\\n    79\\t    \\\"hnswlib-node\\\": \\\"^3.0.0\\\"\\n    80\\t  },\\n    81\\t  \\\"devDependencies\\\": {\\n    82\\t    \\\"@types/node\\\": \\\"^24.0.0\\\",\\n    83\\t    \\\"typescript\\\": \\\"^5.9.0\\\",\\n    84\\t    \\\"vitest\\\": \\\"^4.0.0\\\"\\n    85\\t  },\\n    86\\t  \\\"peerDependencies\\\": {\\n    87\\t    \\\"wednesdayai\\\": \\\"*\\\"\\n    88\\t  },\\n    89\\t  \\\"openclaw\\\": {\\n    90\\t    \\\"extensions\\\": [\\n    91\\t      \\\"./index.ts\\\"\\n    92\\t    ]\\n    93\\t  }\\n    94\\t}\\n    95\\t```\\n    96\\t\\n    97\\t**File:** `extensions/skillweaver/openclaw.plugin.json`\\n    98\\t**Anchor:** new file — create at this path\\n    99\\t**Before:** file does not exist\\n   100\\t**After:**\\n   101\\t```json\\n   102\\t{\\n   103\\t  \\\"id\\\": \\\"skillweaver\\\",\\n   104\\t  \\\"name\\\": \\\"SkillWeaver\\\",\\n   105\\t  \\\"description\\\": \\\"Compositional skill routing: decompose queries, retrieve relevant skills, inject into context via context.collect hook.\\\",\\n   106\\t  \\\"configSchema\\\": {\\n   107\\t    \\\"type\\\": \\\"object\\\",\\n   108\\t    \\\"additionalProperties\\\": false,\\n   109\\t    \\\"properties\\\": {\\n   110\\t      \\\"enabled\\\": {\\n   111\\t        \\\"type\\\": \\\"boolean\\\",\\n   112\\t        \\\"default\\\": true,\\n   113\\t        \\\"description\\\": \\\"Master on/off switch.\\\"\\n   114\\t      },\\n   115\\t      \\\"decomposer\\\": {\\n   116\\t        \\\"type\\\": \\\"object\\\",\\n   117\\t        \\\"additionalProperties\\\": false,\\n   118\\t        \\\"properties\\\": {\\n   119\\t          \\\"provider\\\": {\\n   120\\t            \\\"type\\\": \\\"string\\\",\\n   121\\t            \\\"default\\\": \\\"openrouter\\\",\\n   122\\t            \\\"enum\\\": [\\\"openrouter\\\", \\\"openai\\\", \\\"anthropic\\\", \\\"openai-compatible\\\"],\\n   123\\t            \\\"description\\\": \\\"LLM provider for the decomposition model.\\\"\\n   124\\t          },\\n   125\\t          \\\"model\\\": {\\n   126\\t            \\\"type\\\": \\\"string\\\",\\n   127\\t            \\\"default\\\": \\\"qwen/qwen2.5-7b-instruct\\\",\\n   128\\t            \\\"description\\\": \\\"Model used for query decomposition.\\\"\\n   129\\t          },\\n   130\\t          \\\"apiKey\\\": {\\n   131\\t            \\\"type\\\": \\\"string\\\",\\n   132\\t            \\\"description\\\": \\\"API key override. If null, uses agent's provider credentials.\\\"\\n   133\\t          },\\n   134\\t          \\\"baseUrl\\\": {\\n   135\\t            \\\"type\\\": \\\"string\\\",\\n   136\\t            \\\"description\\\": \\\"Base URL for openai-compatible endpoints.\\\"\\n   137\\t          },\\n   138\\t          \\\"temperature\\\": {\\n   139\\t            \\\"type\\\": \\\"number\\\",\\n   140\\t            \\\"default\\\": 0.1,\\n   141\\t            \\\"minimum\\\": 0,\\n   142\\t            \\\"maximum\\\": 2\\n   143\\t          },\\n   144\\t          \\\"maxTokens\\\": {\\n   145\\t            \\\"type\\\": \\\"number\\\",\\n   146\\t            \\\"default\\\": 256,\\n   147\\t            \\\"minimum\\\": 50,\\n   148\\t            \\\"maximum\\\": 1024\\n   149\\t          }\\n   150\\t        }\\n   151\\t      },\\n   152\\t      \\\"embedding\\\": {\\n   153\\t        \\\"type\\\": \\\"object\\\",\\n   154\\t        \\\"additionalProperties\\\": false,\\n   155\\t        \\\"properties\\\": {\\n   156\\t          \\\"backend\\\": {\\n   157\\t            \\\"type\\\": \\\"string\\\",\\n   158\\t            \\\"default\\\": \\\"local\\\",\\n   159\\t            \\\"enum\\\": [\\\"local\\\", \\\"cloud\\\", \\\"custom\\\"],\\n   160\\t            \\\"description\\\": \\\"Embedding backend: local (Xenova/transformers), cloud (OpenAI), custom (OpenAI-compatible endpoint).\\\"\\n   161\\t          },\\n   162\\t          \\\"model\\\": {\\n   163\\t            \\\"type\\\": \\\"string\\\",\\n   164\\t            \\\"default\\\": \\\"all-MiniLM-L6-v2\\\",\\n   165\\t            \\\"description\\\": \\\"Model name for the local backend.\\\"\\n   166\\t          },\\n   167\\t          \\\"cloudModel\\\": {\\n   168\\t            \\\"type\\\": \\\"string\\\",\\n   169\\t            \\\"default\\\": \\\"text-embedding-3-small\\\",\\n   170\\t            \\\"description\\\": \\\"Model name for the cloud (OpenAI) backend.\\\"\\n   171\\t          },\\n   172\\t          \\\"endpoint\\\": {\\n   173\\t            \\\"type\\\": \\\"string\\\",\\n   174\\t            \\\"description\\\": \\\"OpenAI-compatible endpoint URL for the custom backend.\\\"\\n   175\\t          },\\n   176\\t          \\\"apiKey\\\": {\\n   177\\t            \\\"type\\\": \\\"string\\\",\\n   178\\t            \\\"description\\\": \\\"API key for the custom backend.\\\"\\n   179\\t          }\\n   180\\t        }\\n   181\\t      },\\n   182\\t      \\\"retrieval\\\": {\\n   183\\t        \\\"type\\\": \\\"object\\\",\\n   184\\t        \\\"additionalProperties\\\": false,\\n   185\\t        \\\"properties\\\": {\\n   186\\t          \\\"topK\\\": {\\n   187\\t            \\\"type\\\": \\\"integer\\\",\\n   188\\t            \\\"default\\\": 3,\\n   189\\t            \\\"minimum\\\": 1,\\n   190\\t            \\\"maximum\\\": 10,\\n   191\\t            \\\"description\\\": \\\"Number of skills returned per sub-task.\\\"\\n   192\\t          },\\n   193\\t          \\\"hintSize\\\": {\\n   194\\t            \\\"type\\\": \\\"integer\\\",\\n   195\\t            \\\"default\\\": 15,\\n   196\\t            \\\"minimum\\\": 5,\\n   197\\t            \\\"maximum\\\": 50,\\n   198\\t            \\\"description\\\": \\\"Total hints passed to SAD Pass-2.\\\"\\n   199\\t          },\\n   200\\t          \\\"minQueryLength\\\": {\\n   201\\t            \\\"type\\\": \\\"integer\\\",\\n   202\\t            \\\"default\\\": 20,\\n   203\\t            \\\"minimum\\\": 5,\\n   204\\t            \\\"maximum\\\": 500,\\n   205\\t            \\\"description\\\": \\\"Skip routing for queries shorter than this.\\\"\\n   206\\t          }\\n   207\\t        }\\n   208\\t      },\\n   209\\t      \\\"sad\\\": {\\n   210\\t        \\\"type\\\": \\\"object\\\",\\n   211\\t        \\\"additionalProperties\\\": false,\\n   212\\t        \\\"properties\\\": {\\n   213\\t          \\\"enabled\\\": {\\n   214\\t            \\\"type\\\": \\\"boolean\\\",\\n   215\\t            \\\"default\\\": true,\\n   216\\t            \\\"description\\\": \\\"Enable SAD (2-pass). False = Pass-1 only.\\\"\\n   217\\t          },\\n   218\\t          \\\"maxIterations\\\": {\\n   219\\t            \\\"type\\\": \\\"integer\\\",\\n   220\\t            \\\"default\\\": 1,\\n   221\\t            \\\"minimum\\\": 1,\\n   222\\t            \\\"maximum\\\": 5,\\n   223\\t            \\\"description\\\": \\\"Max SAD iterations (V1 capped at 1).\\\"\\n   224\\t          }\\n   225\\t        }\\n   226\\t      }\\n   227\\t    }\\n   228\\t  },\\n   229\\t  \\\"uiHints\\\": {\\n   230\\t    \\\"enabled\\\": {\\n   231\\t      \\\"label\\\": \\\"Enable SkillWeaver\\\",\\n   232\\t      \\\"help\\\": \\\"Master on/off switch for automatic skill routing.\\\"\\n   233\\t    },\\n   234\\t    \\\"decomposer.provider\\\": {\\n   235\\t      \\\"label\\\": \\\"Decomposer Provider\\\",\\n   236\\t      \\\"help\\\": \\\"LLM provider for the decomposition model.\\\"\\n   237\\t    },\\n   238\\t    \\\"decomposer.model\\\": {\\n   239\\t      \\\"label\\\": \\\"Decomposer Model\\\",\\n   240\\t      \\\"help\\\": \\\"Model used for query decomposition (smaller/cheaper recommended).\\\"\\n   241\\t    },\\n   242\\t    \\\"embedding.backend\\\": {\\n   243\\t      \\\"label\\\": \\\"Embedding Backend\\\",\\n   244\\t      \\\"help\\\": \\\"Where to compute embeddings: locally, via OpenAI cloud, or custom endpoint.\\\"\\n   245\\t    },\\n   246\\t    \\\"sad.enabled\\\": {\\n   247\\t      \\\"label\\\": \\\"SAD (2-Pass)\\\",\\n   248\\t      \\\"help\\\": \\\"Enable Skill-Aware Decomposition for improved accuracy.\\\"\\n   249\\t    }\\n   250\\t  }\\n   251\\t}\\n   252\\t```\\n   253\\t\\n   254\\t**File:** `extensions/skillweaver/tsconfig.json`\\n   255\\t**Anchor:** new file — create at this path\\n   256\\t**Before:** file does not exist\\n   257\\t**After:**\\n   258\\t```json\\n   259\\t{\\n   260\\t  \\\"compilerOptions\\\": {\\n   261\\t    \\\"target\\\": \\\"ES2023\\\",\\n   262\\t    \\\"module\\\": \\\"NodeNext\\\",\\n   263\\t    \\\"moduleResolution\\\": \\\"NodeNext\\\",\\n   264\\t    \\\"strict\\\": true,\\n   265\\t    \\\"esModuleInterop\\\": true,\\n   266\\t    \\\"outDir\\\": \\\"./dist\\\",\\n   267\\t    \\\"rootDir\\\": \\\".\\\",\\n   268\\t    \\\"declaration\\\": true,\\n   269\\t    \\\"sourceMap\\\": true,\\n   270\\t    \\\"skipLibCheck\\\": true,\\n   271\\t    \\\"forceConsistentCasingInFileNames\\\": true,\\n   272\\t    \\\"resolveJsonModule\\\": true,\\n   273\\t    \\\"paths\\\": {\\n   274\\t      \\\"wednesdayai/plugin-sdk\\\": [\\\"./node_modules/wednesdayai/dist/plugin-sdk/index.js\\\"]\\n   275\\t    }\\n   276\\t  },\\n   277\\t  \\\"include\\\": [\\\"./**/*.ts\\\"],\\n   278\\t  \\\"exclude\\\": [\\\"node_modules\\\", \\\"dist\\\"]\\n   279\\t}\\n   280\\t```\\n   281\\t\\n   282\\t## Allowed moves\\n   283\\t\\n   284\\tCreate exactly the three files listed in `files:`. No other files. No edits to existing files.\\n   285\\t\\n   286\\t## STOP triggers\\n   287\\t\\n   288\\t- Any of the three file paths already exist\\n   289\\t- package.json `name` is not `@wednesdayai/skillweaver`\\n   290\\t- openclaw.plugin.json `id` is not `\\\"skillweaver\\\"`\\n   291\\t- test fails to parse any file as valid JSON\\n   292\\t\\n   293\\t## Done when\\n   294\\t\\n   295\\t`WAI_TYPECHECK_CMD=\\\"cd extensions/skillweaver && pnpm exec tsc --noEmit\\\" WAI_TEST_CMD=\\\"cd extensions/skillweaver && npx vitest run package.test.ts\\\" bash ~/.claude/wai/scripts/task-gate.sh plugin-skillweaver 001` exits 0     1\\t---\\n     2\\tid: \\\"002\\\"\\n     3\\tphase: 1\\n     4\\ttitle: Create config schema resolver, validator, and skills-mode checker\\n     5\\tstatus: ready\\n     6\\tdepends_on: [\\\"001\\\"]\\n     7\\tparallel: false\\n     8\\tconflicts_with: []\\n     9\\tfiles:\\n    10\\t  - extensions/skillweaver/src/config.ts\\n    11\\tirreversible: false\\n    12\\tscope_test: \\\"extensions/skillweaver/src/config.test.ts\\\"\\n    13\\tallowed_change: create\\n    14\\tcovers_criteria: [SC6]\\n    15\\t---\\n    16\\t## Failing test (write first)\\n    17\\t\\n    18\\tCreate `extensions/skillweaver/src/config.test.ts`:\\n    19\\t\\n    20\\t```ts\\n    21\\timport { describe, it, expect } from \\\"vitest\\\";\\n    22\\timport { resolveConfig, checkSkillsMode, validateConfig } from \\\"./config.js\\\";\\n    23\\t\\n    24\\tconst defaults = {\\n    25\\t  enabled: true,\\n    26\\t  decomposer: { provider: \\\"openrouter\\\", model: \\\"qwen/qwen2.5-7b-instruct\\\", temperature: 0.1, maxTokens: 256 },\\n    27\\t  embedding: { backend: \\\"local\\\", model: \\\"all-MiniLM-L6-v2\\\", cloudModel: \\\"text-embedding-3-small\\\" },\\n    28\\t  retrieval: { topK: 3, hintSize: 15, minQueryLength: 20 },\\n    29\\t  sad: { enabled: true, maxIterations: 1 },\\n    30\\t};\\n    31\\t\\n    32\\tdescribe(\\\"resolveConfig\\\", () => {\\n    33\\t  it(\\\"fills defaults for empty input\\\", () => {\\n    34\\t    expect(resolveConfig({})).toEqual(defaults);\\n    35\\t  });\\n    36\\t\\n    37\\t  it(\\\"merges partial overrides\\\", () => {\\n    38\\t    const result = resolveConfig({ retrieval: { topK: 5 } });\\n    39\\t    expect(result.retrieval.topK).toBe(5);\\n    40\\t    expect(result.retrieval.hintSize).toBe(15); // default preserved\\n    41\\t  });\\n    42\\t\\n    43\\t  it(\\\"preserves decomposer overrides\\\", () => {\\n    44\\t    const result = resolveConfig({ decomposer: { model: \\\"gpt-4o-mini\\\", provider: \\\"openai\\\", temperature: 0.2, maxTokens: 128 } });\\n    45\\t    expect(result.decomposer.model).toBe(\\\"gpt-4o-mini\\\");\\n    46\\t    expect(result.decomposer.temperature).toBe(0.2);\\n    47\\t  });\\n    48\\t});\\n    49\\t\\n    50\\tdescribe(\\\"validateConfig\\\", () => {\\n    51\\t  it(\\\"rejects invalid backend\\\", () => {\\n    52\\t    expect(() => validateConfig({ embedding: { backend: \\\"invalid\\\" } } as never))\\n    53\\t      .toThrow(/backend/);\\n    54\\t  });\\n    55\\t\\n    56\\t  it(\\\"rejects invalid decomposer provider\\\", () => {\\n    57\\t    expect(() => validateConfig({ decomposer: { provider: \\\"gemini\\\" } } as never))\\n    58\\t      .toThrow(/provider/);\\n    59\\t  });\\n    60\\t\\n    61\\t  it(\\\"accepts valid config\\\", () => {\\n    62\\t    expect(() => validateConfig(defaults)).not.toThrow();\\n    63\\t  });\\n    64\\t});\\n    65\\t\\n    66\\tdescribe(\\\"checkSkillsMode\\\", () => {\\n    67\\t  it(\\\"returns 'default' when skills mode is default or missing\\\", () => {\\n    68\\t    const result = checkSkillsMode({});\\n    69\\t    expect(result).toBe(\\\"default\\\");\\n    70\\t  });\\n    71\\t\\n    72\\t  it(\\\"returns 'names' when configured\\\", () => {\\n    73\\t    const result = checkSkillsMode({ agents: { defaults: { systemPrompt: { sections: { skills: \\\"names\\\" } } } } });\\n    74\\t    expect(result).toBe(\\\"names\\\");\\n    75\\t  });\\n    76\\t\\n    77\\t  it(\\\"returns 'off' when disabled\\\", () => {\\n    78\\t    const result = checkSkillsMode({ agents: { defaults: { systemPrompt: { sections: { skills: \\\"off\\\" } } } } });\\n    79\\t    expect(result).toBe(\\\"off\\\");\\n    80\\t  });\\n    81\\t\\n    82\\t  it(\\\"detects 'compact' mode\\\", () => {\\n    83\\t    const result = checkSkillsMode({ agents: { defaults: { systemPrompt: { sections: { skills: \\\"compact\\\" } } } });\\n    84\\t    expect(result).toBe(\\\"compact\\\");\\n    85\\t  });\\n    86\\t});\\n    87\\t```\\n    88\\t\\n    89\\t## Change\\n    90\\t\\n    91\\t**File:** `extensions/skillweaver/src/config.ts`\\n    92\\t**Anchor:** new file — create at this path\\n    93\\t**Before:** file does not exist\\n    94\\t**After:**\\n    95\\t```ts\\n    96\\texport interface SkillWeaverConfig {\\n    97\\t  enabled: boolean;\\n    98\\t  decomposer: {\\n    99\\t    provider: \\\"openrouter\\\" | \\\"openai\\\" | \\\"anthropic\\\" | \\\"openai-compatible\\\";\\n   100\\t    model: string;\\n   101\\t    apiKey?: string | null;\\n   102\\t    baseUrl?: string | null;\\n   103\\t    temperature: number;\\n   104\\t    maxTokens: number;\\n   105\\t  };\\n   106\\t  embedding: {\\n   107\\t    backend: \\\"local\\\" | \\\"cloud\\\" | \\\"custom\\\";\\n   108\\t    model: string;\\n   109\\t    cloudModel: string;\\n   110\\t    endpoint?: string | null;\\n   111\\t    apiKey?: string | null;\\n   112\\t  };\\n   113\\t  retrieval: {\\n   114\\t    topK: number;\\n   115\\t    hintSize: number;\\n   116\\t    minQueryLength: number;\\n   117\\t  };\\n   118\\t  sad: {\\n   119\\t    enabled: boolean;\\n   120\\t    maxIterations: number;\\n   121\\t  };\\n   122\\t}\\n   123\\t\\n   124\\tconst DEFAULTS: SkillWeaverConfig = {\\n   125\\t  enabled: true,\\n   126\\t  decomposer: {\\n   127\\t    provider: \\\"openrouter\\\",\\n   128\\t    model: \\\"qwen/qwen2.5-7b-instruct\\\",\\n   129\\t    temperature: 0.1,\\n   130\\t    maxTokens: 256,\\n   131\\t  },\\n   132\\t  embedding: {\\n   133\\t    backend: \\\"local\\\",\\n   134\\t    model: \\\"all-MiniLM-L6-v2\\\",\\n   135\\t    cloudModel: \\\"text-embedding-3-small\\\",\\n   136\\t  },\\n   137\\t  retrieval: {\\n   138\\t    topK: 3,\\n   139\\t    hintSize: 15,\\n   140\\t    minQueryLength: 20,\\n   141\\t  },\\n   142\\t  sad: {\\n   143\\t    enabled: true,\\n   144\\t    maxIterations: 1,\\n   145\\t  },\\n   146\\t};\\n   147\\t\\n   148\\tconst VALID_BACKENDS = new Set([\\\"local\\\", \\\"cloud\\\", \\\"custom\\\"]);\\n   149\\tconst VALID_PROVIDERS = new Set([\\\"openrouter\\\", \\\"openai\\\", \\\"anthropic\\\", \\\"openai-compatible\\\"]);\\n   150\\t\\n   151\\texport function resolveConfig(raw: Record<string, unknown>): SkillWeaverConfig {\\n   152\\t  const decomposer = { ...DEFAULTS.decomposer, ...(raw.decomposer as Partial<SkillWeaverConfig[\\\"decomposer\\\"]> ?? {}) };\\n   153\\t  const embedding = { ...DEFAULTS.embedding, ...(raw.embedding as Partial<SkillWeaverConfig[\\\"embedding\\\"]> ?? {}) };\\n   154\\t  const retrieval = { ...DEFAULTS.retrieval, ...(raw.retrieval as Partial<SkillWeaverConfig[\\\"retrieval\\\"]> ?? {}) };\\n   155\\t  const sad = { ...DEFAULTS.sad, ...(raw.sad as Partial<SkillWeaverConfig[\\\"sad\\\"]> ?? {}) };\\n   156\\t  return {\\n   157\\t    ...DEFAULTS,\\n   158\\t    enabled: raw.enabled !== undefined ? Boolean(raw.enabled) : DEFAULTS.enabled,\\n   159\\t    decomposer,\\n   160\\t    embedding,\\n   161\\t    retrieval,\\n   162\\t    sad,\\n   163\\t  };\\n   164\\t}\\n   165\\t\\n   166\\texport function validateConfig(config: SkillWeaverConfig): void {\\n   167\\t  if (!VALID_PROVIDERS.has(config.decomposer.provider)) {\\n   168\\t    throw new Error(`Invalid decomposer provider: ${config.decomposer.provider}`);\\n   169\\t  }\\n   170\\t  if (!VALID_BACKENDS.has(config.embedding.backend)) {\\n   171\\t    throw new Error(`Invalid embedding backend: ${config.embedding.backend}`);\\n   172\\t  }\\n   173\\t  if (config.retrieval.topK < 1 || config.retrieval.topK > 10) {\\n   174\\t    throw new Error(`topK must be 1-10, got ${config.retrieval.topK}`);\\n   175\\t  }\\n   176\\t  if (config.sad.maxIterations < 1 || config.sad.maxIterations > 5) {\\n   177\\t    throw new Error(`maxIterations must be 1-5, got ${config.sad.maxIterations}`);\\n   178\\t  }\\n   179\\t}\\n   180\\t\\n   181\\ttype SkillsMode = \\\"default\\\" | \\\"compa