{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_32","type":"command_execution","command":"/bin/zsh -lc \"nl -ba /Users/david/.codex/memories/skills/adversarial-review-contract/SKILL.md | sed -n '1,90p'\"","aggregated_output":"     1\t---\n     2\tname: adversarial-review-contract\n     3\tdescription: Use for read-only adversarial reviews where the user wants exact anchors, live-source verification, terse findings, and a fixed verdict contract.\n     4\targument-hint: \"[spec-or-task-scope]\"\n     5\tuser-invocable: false\n     6\tallowed-tools:\n     7\t  - Read\n     8\t  - Grep\n     9\t  - Bash\n    10\t---\n    11\t\n    12\t# Adversarial Review Contract\n    13\t\n    14\tUse this when the user asks for read-only review language such as \"adversarial review\", \"read-only\", \"no file edits\", \"do not infer\", \"grep and read\", \"find every way this fails\", or requires exact anchors/citations.\n    15\t\n    16\tDo not use this for implementation tasks or for reviews that allow speculative design advice.\n    17\t\n    18\t## Inputs / context to gather\n    19\t\n    20\t1. Read the user prompt and extract the exact output contract.\n    21\t2. Read the target spec/task/plan files first.\n    22\t3. Read the exact live repo files or exact git object paths that the review must verify.\n    23\t4. If the user names required commands, run those exact commands and use their output as evidence anchors.\n    24\t5. If this is a re-review, read the prior review or decision log only after you know the current task scope.\n    25\t6. If the review is governed by a spec or success-criteria doc, extract that checklist up front and use it as the coverage map for the review.\n    26\t\n    27\t## Procedure\n    28\t\n    29\t1. Lock mode to read-only.\n    30\t   - Do not edit files.\n    31\t   - Do not propose code changes as if they were already verified.\n    32\t2. Build a verification table before writing findings.\n    33\t   - Task/spec anchor.\n    34\t   - Live source path and line.\n    35\t   - Status: correct, incomplete, drifted, or missing.\n    36\t3. Verify anchors against the live repo, not just plan prose.\n    37\t   - Grep the exact anchor text first.\n    38\t   - If the file or anchor is missing, say so explicitly.\n    39\t4. Trace the runtime consequence for any nontrivial finding.\n    40\t   - Example: if a merge plan moves features, also inspect the read path that decides visibility.\n    41\t5. For seam-heavy data flows, trace both the write path and every public read/query surface that can surface the behavior.\n    42\t   - Typical seam order: normalization, storage codec/insert bindings, hydration/replay, then public read or recall APIs.\n    43\t6. Drop weak claims.\n    44\t   - If a claim lacks an exact citation, remove it.\n    45\t   - If a claim depends on inference beyond the spec/diff/source, downgrade it or drop it.\n    46\t7. For re-reviews, grep nearby plan files for stale drift.\n    47\t   - Check top-level `plan.md`, decision logs, sibling tasks, and ledger text when the user asks for \"new inconsistency\" or \"all references gone\".\n    48\t8. Write the final answer in the exact requested format.\n    49\t   - Findings first.\n    50\t   - Terse wording.\n    51\t   - Exactly one verdict line in the requested wording.\n    52\t\n    53\t## Efficiency plan\n    54\t\n    55\t- Start with the user-named files and commands; do not roam the repo first.\n    56\t- Use fixed-string grep for anchors before opening large files.\n    57\t- Cache the exact paths and line numbers for each finding in a scratch list so you do not have to re-open the same files.\n    58\t- Stop searching a candidate issue once it loses citation support; move to the next axis.\n    59\t\n    60\t## Pitfalls and fixes\n    61\t\n    62\t- Symptom: the review sounds persuasive but has no surviving findings.\n    63\t  - Cause: claims were not tied to exact lines.\n    64\t  - Fix: enforce \"no citation, no finding.\"\n    65\t- Symptom: the task file looks corrected but the plan is still inconsistent.\n    66\t  - Cause: only the named task file was checked.\n    67\t  - Fix: grep the wider plan tree for semantic drift.\n    68\t- Symptom: an anchor matches, but the implementation would still fail.\n    69\t  - Cause: anchor-only verification missed downstream runtime behavior.\n    70\t  - Fix: inspect the live read/query path affected by the change.\n    71\t- Symptom: a storage/query feature looks correct in one seam but still fails the success criteria.\n    72\t  - Cause: only one branch or one consumer was inspected.\n    73\t  - Fix: map the spec criteria first, then walk string vs array branches and each public consumer that can expose the data.\n    74\t- Symptom: output drifts into praise or summary.\n    75\t  - Cause: the fixed review contract was not followed.\n    76\t  - Fix: write only concrete findings plus the exact verdict line.\n    77\t\n    78\t## Verification checklist\n    79\t\n    80\t- The answer stays read-only.\n    81\t- Every finding cites the exact task/spec anchor and the exact source or git-output line.\n    82\t- When a spec defines success criteria, the reviewed findings explicitly cover or defer each relevant criterion.\n    83\t- Missing files or anchors are called out explicitly.\n    84\t- Plan-text conclusions are separated from source-backed verification when the user asks for that distinction.\n    85\t- The final line uses the exact verdict wording requested by the user.\n    86\t\n    87\t## Minimal usage example\n    88\t\n    89\tIf the user asks for a read-only adversarial review of `$ARGUMENTS`:\n    90\t\n","exit_code":0,"status":"completed"}}
